_title        =\n|population_blank2              =\n|population_density_blank1_km2 =   \n|population_density_blank1_sq_mi =\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|location = 18\u00b048\u203244\u2033N 98\u00b057\u203221\u2033E\n|timezone               = {{Interlanguage link multi|Tiempo_del_Centro|es}}\n|utc_offset             = -6\n|timezone_DST           = ''[[Time in Mexico|Tiempo del Centro]]''\n|utc_offset_DST         = -5\n|coordinates            = {{coord|18|48|44|N|99|57|21|W|region:MX|display=inline}}\n|elevation_footnotes    =  <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_ft           =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type       =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            = 62740 - 62759\n|area_code              = 735\n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|blank1_name            =\n|blank1_info            =\n|website                = http://www.cuautla.gob.mx\n|footnotes              =\n}}\n'''Cuautla''' ({{IPA-nah|\u02c8k\u02b7a\u028dt\u0361\u026ca}}, meaning \"where the eagles roam\"), officially '''La heroica e hist\u00f3rica Cuautla, Morelos''' (''The Heroic and Historic Cuautla, Morelos'') or '''H. H. Cuautla, Morelos''', is a city and [[municipalities of Mexico|municipality]] in the [[Mexican state]] of [[Morelos]], about 104 kilometers south of [[Mexico City]]. In the 2010 census the city population was 154,358.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypopulation.de/php/mexico-morelos.php?cityid=170060001|title=Cuautla de Morelos (Cuautla, Morelos, Mexico) - Population Statistics, Charts, Map, Location, Weather and Web Information|website=www.citypopulation.de}}</ref> The municipality covers 153.651&nbsp;km\u00b2 (59.325 sq mi). Cuautla is the third most populous city in the state, after [[Cuernavaca]] and [[Jiutepec]]. The city was founded on 4 April 1829.<ref>http://siglo.inafed.gob.mx/enciclopedia/EMM17morelos/municipios/17006a.html Retrieved Dec 18, 2018.</ref>\n\nThe Cuautla Metropolitan Area, the second largest in [[Morelos]], comprises the municipalities of Cuautla, Yautepec, Ayala, [[Yecapixtla]], [[Atlatlahucan]], and [[Tlayacapan]]. It covers 1,037.30 km<sup>2</sup>, which represents 21.26% of the state's total area. The metropolitan population (2010) is 434,187.<ref>http://coespo.morelos.gob.mx/Boletines/zona-metropolitana-cuautla Retrieved Dec 18, 2018.</ref>\n\n==History==\n[http://siglo.inafed.gob.mx/enciclopedia/EMM17morelos/municipios/17006a.html inafed.gob.mx/Cuautla (Dec 18, 2018)]\n===Prehispanic History===\nThe [[Olmec]] group who lived in [[Chalcatzingo]] (southeast of Cuautla) founded settlements in Cuautla, Tepalcingo, Jonacatepec (Las Pilas), Olintepec, Atlihuayan, Huaxtepec, Gualupita de Cuernavaca, Tlayacapan, etc. (Pi\u00f1a Chan y Plancarte). \n\nFive years after the conquest of ''Cuahunahu\u00e1c'' (Cuernavaca) (1379 CE)<ref>http://morelos.gob.mx/?q=cuernavaca (Dec 18, 2018)</ref>, [[Moctezuma Ilhuicamina]] conquered Huaxtepec ([[Oaxtepec]]), Yautepec, Tlayacapan and other towns of Morelos and Guerrero. With Huaxtepec, which was the prehispanic and colonial capital of the peoples of the ''Plan de Amilpas'', its 25-human settlements including ''Cuauhtl\u00e1n'', had to pay tribute of 400 cotton blankets, 400 two-color valances, 400 bedspreads, 800 thin cotton blankets, 400 pairs of shorts (''patees''), 200 women's shirts, and 1,200 veils (''mantillas'') every 80 days. In addition, they were required to contribute labor.\n\n===Spanish Conquest & Colonial Period===\nThe ''Plan de Amilpas'' including Cuautla was conquered by Captain ''Gonzalo de Sandoval'' on March 14, 1521. \n\nAfter the conquest, Indigenous lands were confiscated, mostly for sugar cane plantations and mills (''trapiches''). Despite Indigenous protests, Viceroy ''Gaspar de Zuniga Acevedo'' ruled in favor of the colonists on July 5, 1603. As the region prospered, Cuautla was named ''Alcalde Mayor'' and separated from Oaxtepec.\n\nConstruction of the church of ''Santo Domingo'' began in the middle of the 16th century. The church and monastery of ''San Diego'' were begun by [[Franciscan]] Friars in 1640.\n\n===Independence & 19th Century===\nAfter a number of successful battles, General [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Morelos]] arrived in Cuautla in December 1811. On February 19, 1812, Spanish General [[F\u00e9lix Mar\u00eda Calleja]] began the 72-day [[Siege of Cuautla]]. Morelos was accompanied by ''Leonardo Bravo'', [[Mariano Matamoros]], [[Hermenegildo Galeana]], [[Nicol\u00e1s Bravo]], and [[Manuel de Ordiera]]. 12-year-old [[Narciso Mendoza]], known as the ''Ni\u00f1o Artillero'' (Child Gunner) is remembered for stopping an advance of royalist troops by setting off a cannon. Morelos and his army were able to break out on May 2, 1812.\n\nCuautla was designated a ''Heroic City'' (''Heroica Ciudad de Morelos'') on April 4, 1829, while Felipe B. Montero was ''Presidente Municipal'' (mayor).\n\nAn 1865 photograph shows the construction of the second floor of the ''Palacio Municipal'' (city hall) in 1865. The building was burned during the Revolution.<ref>http://revista.morelos.gob.mx/conociendo-morelos/cuautla-ciudad-historica-heroica-y-hermosa Retrieved Dec 18, 2018.</ref>\n\nThe railroad station was opened on June 18, 1881, next to the ''Convento de San Diego''.<ref>http://revista.morelos.gob.mx/conociendo-morelos/cuautla-ciudad-historica-heroica-y-hermosa (Dec 18, 2918(</ref> Tourist trains continue to operate along the line.<ref>http://www.morelosturistico.com/espanol/pagina/z_655_tren_escenico_de_cuautla.php (Retrieved Dec 18, 2018)</ref>\n\n===Revolution & 20th Century===\nAs a young man, [[Emiliano Zapata]] was concerned about land seizures in Anenecuilco, his hometown. In May 1911 he answered [[Francisco I. Madero]]'s call to arms against President [[Porfirio D\u00edaz]]. After minor battles in ''Chietla, Iz\u00facar, Metepec'' and ''Atlixco'', Puebla; and ''Yautepec'' and ''Jonacatepec'' in Morelos, he arrived at Cuautla on May 11, 1911. With 4,000 or 5,000 troops he surrounded the city, and the week-long [[Battle of Cuautla (1911)]] began.<ref>https://www.portaloaca.com/historia/biografias/47-biografia-de-emiliano-zapata.html (Dec 18, 2018)</ref> The battle was a major turning point in the [[Mexican Revolution]], as Porfirio D\u00edaz said the battle convinced him to sign the [[Treaty of Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez]] and resign.\n\nNearly seven years later, in April 1919, Colonel ''Jesus Guajardo'' assassinated Zapata, apparently under orders of President [[Venustiano Carranza]] in [[Chinameca, Ciudad Ayala|Chinameca, Ayala]]. His body was placed on a mule and left on the street before he was brought to Cuautla for burial.<ref>https://www.portaloaca.com/historia/biografias/47-biografia-de-emiliano-zapata.html Retrieved Dec 18, 2018.</ref>\n\n===21st Century===\nSix people, including an 11-year-old child, were killed in the September 17, [[2017 Puebla earthquake]].<ref>https://www.launion.com.mx/morelos/avances/noticias/113372-reportes-rapidos-despues-del-sismo-de-7-1.html Retrieved Dec 17, 2018.</ref>\n\nJesus Corona Damian of ''Juntos Haremos Historia'' (Together we will make history coalition) was elected Presidente Municipal (mayor) in the election of July 1, 2018.<ref>http://impepac.mx/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Candidatos-electos-2018.pdf Retrieved Dec 14, 2018</ref>\n\n[[Tetelcingo]] was scheduled to become an autonomous municipality on January 1, 2019,<ref>https://www.diariodemorelos.com/noticias/habr%C3%A1-partir-de-2019-4-municipios-ind%C3%ADgenas-en-morelos (Dec 20, 2018)</ref> but Cuautla authorities objected.<ref>https://www.elsoldecuautla.com.mx/local/tetelcingo-no-sera-municipio-indigena-1942639.html accessed Dec 27, 2018</ref><ref>https://www.diariodemorelos.com/noticias/no-hay-marcha-atr-s-contra-municipalizaci-n-de-tetelcingo-ratifica-alcalde-de-cuautla accessed Dec 27, 2018</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Celebrations===\n\n* 6 January: [[Epiphany (holiday)|D\u00eda de Reyes]]\n* 5 February: [[Constitution Day|D\u00eda de la Constituci\u00f3n]]\n* 19 February: Anniversary of the start of 1812 siege of Cuautla \n* 8 March: [[International Women's Day|D\u00eda Internacional de la Mujer]]\n* Fair of the second Friday of Lent, considered the second in importance of the state (variable date).<ref>http://revista.morelos.gob.mx/conociendo-morelos/cuautla-ciudad-historica-heroica-y-hermosa Retrieved Dec 18, 2018.</ref>\n* April 10, commemoration of the death of Emiliano Zapata.\n* 2 May: Anniversary of the end of 1812 siege of Cuautla [[Siege of Cuautla]] \n* 16 September: Mexican Independence Day [[Cry of Dolores]]\n* 30 September: Anniversary of the birth of the General [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Morelos y Pav\u00f3n]] There is a parade.\n* 8 August: Anniversary of the birth of the General [[Emiliano Zapata]] Salazar\n* 2 November: [[Day of the Dead]]\n\n===Leather, Crafts, & Textiles===\n* Cuautla is distinguished by its ''huaracher\u00eda'' (leather sandals)\n* Tetelcingo is known for the elaboration of wire birdcages, bread boxes, and lace napkin Women in Tetelcingo wear traditional Indigenous dress, consisting of a navy blue ''huipil'' (skirt) and a ''chincuete'' that is girded at the waist with a belt loom weaved by the Indians themselves. There are several workshops that are dedicated to saddlery, the manufacture of huaraches, belts, saddles and all the necessary equipment for riding.\n\n===Food===\nRich stews with green or red ''guasmole'', the green mole of ''pipi\u00e1n'' with tamales, and cecina. Also ''huitlacoche molotes'', a squash flower soup (''sopa de flor de calabaza''), or a mushroom cream soup, or Aztec soup. Also available is Morelense chicken with peanut sauce, ''Tzompantli'' flower pancakes, and broken beans (''frijoles quebrados'').<ref>http://revista.morelos.gob.mx/conociendo-morelos/cuautla-ciudad-historica-heroica-y-hermosa Retrieved Dec 18, 2018.</ref>\n\n===Art===\n''Motivos sobre el agua'', (Motifs on water) is a fresco painted by Olga Costa and Jos\u00e9 Ch\u00e1vez Morado, hidden inside the Agua Hedionda Spa. There is a group of plump mermaids playing musical instruments at the bottom of the sea. One carries the zither, another the cello, and one a type of shell or tambourine. They are surrounded by fish, shells, corals and marine stars. It was made in 1952.<ref>http://revista.morelos.gob.mx/conociendo-morelos/cuautla-ciudad-historica-heroica-y-hermosa Retrieved Dec 18, 2018.</ref>\n\n===Dance===\n''Las Tetelcingas'' is a traditional dance from the town of that name.<ref>http://revista.morelos.gob.mx/conociendo-morelos/cuautla-ciudad-historica-heroica-y-hermosa Retrieved Dec 18, 2018.</ref>\n\nTypical dress: the authentic suit is that of ''tetelcinga'', which consists of a huipil and a tangle of thick dark blue cloth, tied at the waist with wide folds by means of a blue and red sash. Eliseo Arag\u00f3n said that half a century ago some women still used to paint their hair in blue, red or green, to the Olmec. It is also said that the same cup in which they drank water and consumed their food, used it on the head as an ornament.\n\nThe man's costume is currently the one used anywhere, however, there are photographs in which the natives of Tetelcingo wear a kind of jorongo and short leather pants.\n\n==Economy==\nAmong the most important activities in Cuautla you will find:\n*Agriculture (corn, beans)\n*Livestock (beef, pork)\n*Nursery (production of ornamental plants and fruit trees)\n*Aquaculture (production of aquatic species such as mojarras, prawns, and catfish.\n*Agroindustry (sugar cane)\n*General Commerce (financial, administrative and real estate services, premises such as stationery, grocery, food, beverages, etc.)\n*Services (hotel, restaurant, professional, technical, and personal)\n*Tourism (natural areas, lodging, restaurants, bars, nightclubs, water parks, spas, and springs.)<ref>http://www.cuautla.mx/economia Retrieved Dec 18, 2018.</ref>\n*Construction. \n*Manufacturing. \n\nThe Cuautla Industrial Park, located in Ayala, covers 130 ha and is the second largest in Morelos. Most of the companies are related to the automotive industry. The largest employers are ''Saint-Gobainl'', (glass), ''Sekurit'' (windshields), and ''Temic'' (industrial parts).<ref>http://www.municipios.mx/morelos/cuautla/ Retrieved Dec 18, 2018.</ref><ref>http://parquesindustrialesmorelos.com/parques-industriales/parque-industrial-cuautla/ Retrieved Dec 18, 2018.</ref>\n\nRiverside, CA is a Sister City.<ref>https://www.riversideca.gov/mayor/international-relations/sister-cities Retrieved Dec 18, 2018.</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\n''Highways''\n\n*160 (4 lanes) west to Cocoyoc-Yautepec-Jiutepec-Cuernavaca; east to Jantetelco-Izucar de Matamoros\n*115D (tollway) northwest to Oaxtepec-Tepoztlan-La Pera 95D ''north'' to Mexico City; ''south'' to Cuernavaca-Acapulco\n*115 north to Tetelteco, then north to Tepetlixpa-Atlatahucan-Mexico City OR 115D (tollway) north to Mexico City OR south on ''La Villa'' to Ayala-Galeana-Jojutla.\n\n''Public Transportation''\n\nLocal buses, referred to as \"combis,\" serve Cuautla and nearby municipalities. Also, taxis are available. \n\nCuautla has several bus terminals for long-distance travel:\n*Oro (mostly points east: state Puebla, plus Cuernavaca & eastern Morelos, parts of Oaxaca, Tlaxcala, & Guerrero)\n*Estrella Roja (TER) (Cuernavaca, Mexico City, Airport, Puebla)\n*Pullman de Morelos (Mexico City, Airport, destinations in most parts state of Morelos)\n*Omnibus Crist\u00f3bal Col\u00f3n (OCC) Company based in Cuautla, with service to Taxque\u00f1a and Central Norte (Mexico City), Oaxaca, and Veracruz.\n\nThere is no train service. Airports are located in Cuernavaca (Temixco), Mexico City, and [[Puebla (city)|Puebla]].\n\n==Communities==\n* ''Cuautla'' is the municipal seat. It is located at an altitude of 1,294 meters (4,249 ft.) and has a population of 154,358.<ref>http://www.mipueblo.mx/17/1250/cuautla/ accessed Dec 27, 2018</ref> Its Sister Cities are [[Renton, Washington]], and [[Riverside, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.travelbymexico.com/blog/16451-ciudades-mexicanas-y-sus-ciudades-hermanas-estadounidenses/|title=Ciudades mexicanas y sus ciudades hermanas estadounidenses|accessdate=Feb 18, 2019|publisher=Sister Cities International|language=Spanish|trans-title=Mexican cities and their American sister cities|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831000730/http://www.travelbymexico.com/blog/16451-ciudades-mexicanas-y-sus-ciudades-hermanas-estadounidenses/|archive-date=August 31, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* ''Ex-Hacienda el Hospital'' is located at an altitude of 1,277 meters and has a population of 2,053.<ref>http://www.mipueblo.mx/17/1250/ex-hacienda-el-hospital/ accessed Dec 27, 2018</ref>\n* ''Narciso Mendoza'' is located at an altitude of 1,345 meters and has a population of 1,612.<ref>http://www.mipueblo.mx/17/1250/narciso-mendoza/ accessed Dec 27, 2018</ref>\n* ''Pe\u00f1a Flores (Palo Verde)'' is located at an altitude of 1,343 meters and has a population of 3,867.<ref>http://www.mipueblo.mx/17/1250/pena-flores-palo-verde/ accessed Dec 7, 2018</ref>\n* ''Puxtla'' is located at an altitude of 1,266 meters and has a population of 1,476.<ref>http://www.mipueblo.mx/17/1250/puxtla/ accessed Dec 27, 2018</ref>\n* [[Tetelcingo]] is a [[Nahuatl]] community located 6 km north of Cuautla. \n\n===Education===\nAs of 2014\u20132015, there are 24 daycare centers with 508 children, 110 preschools with 533 teachers and 7,545 pupils, 101 elementary schools (grades 1-6) with 1,225 teachers and 22,754 pupils, and 42 middle schools (grades 7-9) with 641 teachers and 11,354 pupils<ref name=diagnostico/>\n\n==Geography==\n\n===Location===\nCuautla is located in the eastern Morelos, with the geographic coordinates 18\u00b049' N Latitude and 99\u00b001' E Longitude, with an altitude of 1,294 feet above sea level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mexico.pueblosamerica.com/i/cuautla-3/|title=CUAUTLA (Cuautla, Morelos)|website=pueblosamerica.com}}</ref>\n\nCuautla borders the municipalities of [[Atlatlahucan]], [[Ciudad Ayala|Ayala]], [[Yautepec de Zaragoza|Yautepec]], and [[Yecapixtla]].<ref name=diagnostico/>\n\n===Distance from well-known parts of Mexico===\n*[[Cuernavaca]] - 57.1 km via ''La Pera'' (45 min.), 47.9 km via ''Cuauhnahuac'' (48 min.)<ref>https://distancia.mx/Cuautla-Morelos/Cuernavaca Access Dec 18, 2018.</ref>\n* [[Ciudad de M\u00e9xico]] - 71&nbsp;km<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mx.lasdistancias.com/calcular?from=ciudad+de+mexico&to=cuautla|title=Distancia entre ciudad de mexico y cuautla|website=mx.lasdistancias.com}}</ref>\n* [[Monterrey]] - 777&nbsp;km<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mx.lasdistancias.com/calcular?from=monterrery&to=cuautla|title=Distancia entre monterrery y cuautla|website=mx.lasdistancias.com}}</ref>\n* [[Ciudad Juarez]] - 1,617&nbsp;km<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mx.lasdistancias.com/calcular?from=ciudad+juarez&to=Cuautla%2C+M%C3%A9xico |title=Archived copy |accessdate=22 December 2017 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20150202011353/http://mx.lasdistancias.com/calcular?from=ciudad+juarez&to=Cuautla,+M%C3%A9xico |archivedate=2 February 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Veracruz]] - 299&nbsp;km<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mx.lasdistancias.com/calcular?from=Veracruz&to=cuautla|title=Distancia entre Veracruz y cuautla|website=mx.lasdistancias.com}}</ref>\n* [[Yucatan]] - 1,054&nbsp;km<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mx.lasdistancias.com/calcular?from=yucatan&to=cuautla|title=Distancia entre yucatan y cuautla|website=mx.lasdistancias.com}}</ref> \n* [[Cancun]] - 1,292&nbsp;km<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mx.lasdistancias.com/calcular?from=Canc%C3%BAn%2C+M%C3%A9xico&to=Cuautla%2C+M%C3%A9xico |title=Archived copy |access-date=22 December 2017 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20150202011349/http://mx.lasdistancias.com/calcular?from=Canc%C3%BAn,+M%C3%A9xico&to=Cuautla,+M%C3%A9xico |archive-date=2 February 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Size===\n\nCuautla covers roughly 153.651&nbsp;km\u00b2 (59.32 sq. miles), which is about 3% of the overall size of Morelos.<ref name=\"auto\">[[:es:Cuautla de Morelos]]{{Better source|date=November 2015|reason=[[WP:CIRCULAR]]}}</ref><ref name=diagnostico>{{cite web|url=https://ceieg.morelos.gob.mx/pdf/Diagnosticos2015/CUAUTLA.pdf|title=Cuautla, Diagnostico Municipal 2015|publisher=CEIEG Morelos|accessdate=Feb 26, 2019|language=Spanish|trans-title=Cuautla, Municipal Diagnosis 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Attractions==\n\nThe area is a tourist-friendly region with abundant hot springs and health spas/resorts. It features many archeological sites such as [[Chalcatzingo]] and Indigenous communities such as the [[Tepoztl\u00e1n]] and [[Tetelcingo]] among others. \n\n===Springs, Spas, & Water Parks===\n*[[Agua Hedionda Spa|Agua Hedionda]] ({{lang-es|Stinky Water}}), classified as one of the important water springs of the world due to its chemical composition, is located in Cuautla. These waters have a characteristic smell reminiscent of rotten eggs because of their [[sulfur]] content. The water is 27\u00b0C (80.6\u00b0F), there is a spring, two swimming pools, and a water slide. The mural ''Motivos sobre el agua'' is located in the spa. which was used by ''Olmecas, Teotihuacanos, Chalcas, Tlahuicas'', and ''Aztecas''.[http://balnearioaguahedionda.com/wp/ aguahedionda waterpark]\n*''Balneario Los Limones'' has a spring, swimming pools, wading pool, playground, water slide, picnic area with grills, camping area, fronton court, and a basketball court.<ref>https://www.balneariosenmorelos.com.mx/index.php?q=los_limones (Dec 18, 2018)</ref>\n*''Ejidal spa Cups'' is located in Las Tazas, Cuautlixco. \n*''El Almeal'' is a water park in Cuautla. It has a spring, swimming pools, wading pool, athletic fields, and camping area.<ref>https://morelosturistico.com/espanol/pagina/z_72_Balneario_El_Almeal.php (Dec 18, 2018)</ref>\n*''Spa The Plot'' is a water park in Cuautla at Cuautla-Izucar highway, KM2.\n*''Quinta Manantial'' is a water park with a spring in Cuautla. \u2003\n*''Balneario Agua Linda'' is a public swimming pool.\n*''Erandi Spa'' is a health spa in Cuautla. \u2003\n\n===Museums===\n*The ''Morelos House / Museum'' contains artifacts and descriptions about [[Mexican War of Independence]] from Spain (1812-1821).  It honors Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Morelos, whose rebel troops managed to hold off Royalist troops for 72 days, as well as honoring Emiliano Zapata.<ref>https://www.inah.gob.mx/red-de-museos/228-museo-historico-de-cuautla-casa-de-morelos (Dec 18, 2018)</ref>\n*The Morelos Museum adjoins the old narrow-gauge railroad which was used to haul sugar cane to the local mills. The [http://www.morelosturistico.com/espanol/pagina/z_655_Tren_Escenico_de_Cuautla.php Tren Esc\u00e9nico] is a {{RailGauge|3ft|lk=on}} [[Narrow gauge railway|narrow gauge]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.steamlocomotive.com/lists/searchdb.php?country=MEX&state=MOR|title=Surviving Steam Locomotives in Morelos|website=www.steamlocomotive.com}}</ref> tourist railroad offering train rides pulled by an historic steam locomotive once used by the former [[Interoceanic Railway of Mexico]]. The narrow-gauge was retired in 1973. \n*The tomb of the famous Mexican revolutionary hero [[Emiliano Zapata]] is also located in this city, and every year several festivities are held around the anniversary of his death.\n*The ''Teatro Narciso Mendoza'' is named for the legendary ''Ni\u00f1o Artillero''. This building was inaugurated on January 6, 1952. Today it is a cultural center. There is a 50-meter long mural that tells the history of Cuautla, created by the painter Arturo Estrada, but censored by the religious authority of that time, and covered with white paint.<ref>https://www.mexicoescultura.com/recinto/53757/ (Dec 18, 2018)</ref>\n\n==Architecture==\n\nThe vast majority of buildings in Cuautla, are made of stone and cement with metal rod reinforcements. Also, many homes in this city, are made with only cinder blocks, cement, and a tin roof. Many of these homes also lack electricity and running water. Nearly all homes have a \"tinaco,\" which is a large plastic container for water, which is refilled regularly by the city. These containers let water out into pipes which can be opened or closed to wash clothes and dishes, or to bathe.\n\n==Climate==\n\nThe city is quite warm year-round.\nIn the winter, there is a slight decrease in both the daytime and nighttime temperatures, and because of Cuautla's proximity to the [[Tropic of Cancer]] and its altitude (about 4,500 feet above sea level), the nighttime temperatures year-round usually average about 57&nbsp;\u00b0F (14&nbsp;\u00b0C). On the other hand, because Cuautla is somewhat close to the [[Equator]], temperatures year-round tend to reach into the mid 80s to lower 90s\u00b0F (upper 20s\u00b0C to the lower 30s\u00b0C) even during the winter, and in spring on many days the daytime temperatures may reach well into the upper 90s\u00b0F (upper 30s\u00b0C).<ref>https://weatherspark.com/y/6484/Average-Weather-in-Cuautla-Mexico-Year-Round</ref>\n\n==Religion==\n\nThe dominant religion in Cuautla is Roman Catholicism. There are 22 registered churches in the municipal area.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n[[File:Ex convento de Santo Domingo.jpg|border|right|150x200px|La Iglesia de Santiago Apostol]]\n\n==See also==\n* [http://morelos.gob.mx/?q=cuautla Morelos State site on Cuautla (Spanish)]\n* [[Governor of Morelos|Governors of Morelos]]\n* [http://siglo.inafed.gob.mx/enciclopedia/EMM17morelos/municipios/17006a.html Encyclopedia of Municipalities: Cuautla (Spanish)]\n* [[Siege of Cuautla]]\n* [[Battle of Cuautla (1911)]]\n* [[Quautlatas]]\n* [[List of people from Morelos, Mexico]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{in lang|es}}\n*[https://www.webcitation.org/6EjXaEdST?url=http://www.inegi.gob.mx/est/contenidos/espanol/sistemas/conteo2005/localidad/iter/ 2005 Census population data statistics] INEGI: Instituto Nacional de Estad\u00edstica, Geograf\u00eda e Inform\u00e1tica (National Institute of Statistics, Geography, and Information)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081119042652/http://www.e-local.gob.mx/wb2/ELOCAL/EMM_morelos Morelos] Enciclopedia de los Municipios de M\u00e9xico (Encyclopedia of Mexican Municipalities)\n\n==External links==\n{{in lang|es}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20020926082029/http://www.cuautla.gob.mx/ Ayuntamiento Constitucional de Cuautla (Constitutional Council of Cuautla)] Official website\n\n{{coord|18|49|N|98|57|W|display=title}} \n{{Hero Cities of Mexico}}\n\n{{Morelos}}\n\n[[Category:Municipalities of Morelos]]\n[[Category:People from Morelos]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Morelos]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the Table at Infobox Settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|name          =  Cuautla\n|settlement_type        =Municipal and rural\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            =  <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n|nickname               = \n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline          = mexicopictures 193 0001.jpg\n|imagesize              =300px\n|image_caption          =\n|image_flag             = \n|flag_size              =\n|image_seal             = \n|seal_size              =\n|image_shield           = \n|shield_size            =\n|image_blank_emblem     =\n|blank_emblem_type      =\n|blank_emblem_size      =\n|image_map              = \n|mapsize                = 200px\n|map_caption            = \n|image_map1             = \n|mapsize1               = \n|map_caption1           = \n|image_dot_map          =\n|dot_mapsize            =\n|dot_map_caption        =\n|dot_x =  |dot_y =\n|pushpin_map            = Mexico <!-- the name of a location map as per [[:en:Template:Location_map]] -->\n|pushpin_label