{"title_page": "L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf", "text_new": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name =  L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf I\n| title = [[List of Vietnamese monarchs|King of V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n]]\n| image = Emperor Ly Nam De.jpg\n| caption = Portrait painting of L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf during L\u00ea dynasty era.\n| reign = 544 - 548\n| succession = King of [[V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n]]\n| successor = [[Tri\u1ec7u Vi\u1ec7t V\u01b0\u01a1ng]]\n| consort = [[H\u1ee9a Trinh H\u00f2a]]\n| issue = ?\n| full name = L\u00fd B\u00f4n (\u674e\u8cc1) (also written as L\u00fd B\u00ed)\n| era name = Thi\u00ean \u0110\u1ee9c (\u5929\u5fb7)\n| posthumous name = Emperor Xiaogao of Nam Vi\u1ec7t (\u5357\u8d8a\u5b5d\u9ad8\u7687\u5e1d)\n| temple name = Th\u00e1i T\u1ed5 (\u592a\u7956)\n| house = [[Early L\u00fd Dynasty]]\n| father = L\u00fd C\u1ea1nh\n| mother = L\u00ea Th\u1ecb O\u00e1nh\n| birth_date= 17 October 503\n| death_date = 13 April 548\n| place of burial = Vinh Tomb, [[Lam S\u01a1n (ancient Vietnam)|Lam S\u01a1n]]\n}}\n'''L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf''' ([[ch\u1eef H\u00e1n]]: \u674e\u5357\u5e1d, 17 October 503 \u2013 13 April 548) was a Vietnamese monarch and the founder of [[Name of Vietnam|V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n]]. ruling between 544-8 and the founder of the [[Early L\u00fd Dynasty]].<ref>{{cite book| title=Vietnam Country Map |publisher=Periplus Travel Maps |year=2002&ndash;03 |isbn=0-7946-0070-0}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n\n'''L\u00fd B\u00f4n''' (\u674e\u8cc1) was descended from Chinese refugees who fled [[Wang Mang]]'s seizure of power during the interregnum between the Western and Eastern [[Han dynasty|Han dynasties]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=rCl_02LnNVIC&pg=PA135 Taylor (1983), p. 135]</ref><ref>Walker (2012), p. 134  {{Google books|GBvRs-za0CIC|East Asia: A New History|page=134}}</ref><ref>Catino (2010), p. 142  {{Google books|EL4wX0AFVJEC|The Aggressors: Ho Chi Minh, North Vietnam, and the Communist Bloc|page=142}}</ref><ref>Kohn (2006), p. 308  {{Google books|OIzreCGlHxIC|Dictionary of Wars|page=320}}</ref><ref>Coed\u00e8s (1966), pp. 45\u201346  {{Google books|qgrAFlAC4-QC|The Making of South East Asia|pages=45\u201346}}</ref><ref>Lockhart (2010), p. 221  {{Google books|NYu4JuWyhNcC|The A to Z of Vietnam|page=221}}</ref><ref>West (2009), p. 870  {{Google books|pCiNqFj3MQsC|Encyclopedia of the Peoples of Asia and Oceania|page=870}}</ref> He was a regional magistrate of Giao Ch\u00e2u (\u4ea4\u5dde, [[Chinese language|Chinese]]: Jiaozhou), an area of northern Vietnam roughly corresponding to the area of modern [[Hanoi]]. In 541, during this time China was under constant civil warfare following the [[Southern and Northern Dynasties]] Period, he became increasingly frustrated with the corruption in the government and hostility toward the local population. His friend-general [[Pham Tu]], was an ethnic [[Jie]], help him trained a initial army with 300 cavalry archers and started rebelling against the Liang dynasty. Upon resignation of his post he gathered the local nobility and locals within the [[Red River (Vietnam)|Red River]] Valley (North Vietnam) mobilized the imperial troops and naval fleet of Jiaozhou and successfully expelled the [[Liang Dynasty|Liang]] administration and won a decisive battle in Hofu in summer 543. The following year in February 544, L\u00fd B\u00ed was declared \"Emperor\" by the people with the intention of demonstrating equal in power to China imperial rulers. He renamed the new kingdom \"[[V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n]]\" ([[wikt:\u842c|\u842c]][[wikt:\u6625|\u6625]], literally \"Eternal Spring\"). His imperial armies also repelled attacks from [[Champa]] in the south who had allied with Han's court at the time.\n\n== Further in his life ==\n[[File:Map of V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n Kingdom during Early L\u00fd dynasty.png|left|thumb|220px|Map of V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n Kingdom ]]\nL\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf established his capital at Long Bi\u00ean (modern-day [[Hanoi]]), surrounded himself with effective leadership in military and administrative scholars. L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf was also strongly supported by famous military commander such as [[Ph\u1ea1m Tu]], [[Tri\u1ec7u T\u00fac]], [[Tinh Thi\u1ec1u]], and Tri\u1ec7u Quang Ph\u1ee5c, (son of Tri\u1ec7u Tuc, later known as [[Tri\u1ec7u Vi\u1ec7t V\u01b0\u01a1ng]]).  The latter emerged as a hero in Vietnamese history and eventually succeeded L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf as ruler in 548. L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf built many fortresses at strategic locations throughout V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n to fend off potential threats from Han in the north and from the Champa Kingdom in the south, he also established the first national university for mandarin scholars, implemented land reforms, and promoted literacy amongst the population.  He laid the foundation for many reforms that modelled after the Chinese social structure.\n\n[[File:Emperor Wu of Chen.jpg|222px|thumb|right|[[Emperor Wu of Chen|Tr\u1ea7n B\u00e1 Ti\u00ean]]]]\nStability of V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n did not last long and in October 544, the Liang Dynasty retaliated against V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n by sending 120,000 imperial troops to re-occupy the region.  The Liang emperor sent one of his generals [[Emperor Wu of Chen|Chen Baxian]] (Tr\u1ea7n B\u00e1 Ti\u00ean) and granted him sole command of the invading Liang forces.  By spring of 545, Chen had marched his army into V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n territory and laid [[siege]] and devastation to many cities.  His initial invasion was stalled by L\u00fd imperial forces for months.  However, in the winter of 545, Chen laid a surprised attack on the capital during the monsoon season.  L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf's imperial forces were caught off guard and the imperial administration was forced to abandon Long Bi\u00ean and flee westward into the neighboring kingdom of Laos.  The L\u00fd imperial forces were becoming weary and exhausted and L\u00fd himself was increasingly ill due to months of being exposed in the wilderness.  L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf realized that his illness would not enable him to rally the troops and accomplish a successful resistance against the imperial Chinese forces.  In February 548, he relinquished imperial authority and transferred his power to his older brother [[L\u00fd Thi\u00ean B\u1ea3o]] (co-ruler from 548 until his death in 555) and [[Tri\u1ec7u Vi\u1ec7t V\u01b0\u01a1ng|Tri\u1ec7u Quang Ph\u1ee5c]] (r. 548\u2013571), who was his best [[lieutenant]] and [[general]].\n\nBy April 548, after suffering from serious diseases for months, L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf died in [[Laos]] while fighting the Liang forces when local Laotian tribesmen assassinated him in hope for warding off the invading Liang army. His immediate successor was Tri\u1ec7u Quang Ph\u1ee5c (thereafter known as [[Tri\u1ec7u Vi\u1ec7t V\u01b0\u01a1ng]] which means Trieu Viet King).  The new king continued the resistance and eventually drove the Chinese out from V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n in 550.  Although China occupied Vietnam for approximately 1,000 years, L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf successfully established a Vi\u1ec7t dynasty that gave Northern Vietnam approximately 60 years of independence in between those times.\n\n==Anterior L\u00fd Dynasty==\n* L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf I (r. 542\u2013548)\n* [[L\u00fd Thi\u00ean B\u1ea3o]] (r. 548\u2013555, co-reigned with Tri\u1ec7u Quang Ph\u1ee5c)\n* [[Tri\u1ec7u Vi\u1ec7t V\u01b0\u01a1ng]] (r. 548\u2013571, 555\u2013571 as sole ruler)\n* [[Posterior Hau L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf|L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf II]] (r. 571\u2013602)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Taylor, Keith Weller. (1983). [https://books.google.com/books?id=rCl_02LnNVIC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''The Birth of Vietnam''] (illustrated, reprint ed.). University of California Press. {{ISBN|0520074173}}. Retrieved 7 August 2013.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|Early L\u00fd Dynasty|October 17,|503|April 13,|548}}\n{{s-bef|before=None}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Vietnamese monarchs|Emperor of Nam Vi\u1ec7t]]|years=544\u2013548}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tri\u1ec7u Vi\u1ec7t V\u01b0\u01a1ng]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ly Nam De}}\n[[Category:Early L\u00fd Dynasty Kings]]\n[[Category:503 births]]\n[[Category:548 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox royalty\n| name =  L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf I\n| title = [[List of Vietnamese monarchs|King of V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n]]\n| image = Emperor Ly Nam De.jpg\n| caption = Portrait painting of L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf during L\u00ea dynasty era.\n| reign = 544 - 548\n| succession = King of [[V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n]]\n| successor = [[Tri\u1ec7u Vi\u1ec7t V\u01b0\u01a1ng]]\n| consort = [[H\u1ee9a Trinh H\u00f2a]]\n| issue = ?\n| full name = L\u00fd B\u00f4n (\u674e\u8cc1) (also written as L\u00fd B\u00ed)\n| era name = Thi\u00ean \u0110\u1ee9c (\u5929\u5fb7)\n| posthumous name = Emperor Xiaogao of Nam Vi\u1ec7t (\u5357\u8d8a\u5b5d\u9ad8\u7687\u5e1d)\n| temple name = Th\u00e1i T\u1ed5 (\u592a\u7956)\n| house = [[Early L\u00fd Dynasty]]\n| father = L\u00fd C\u1ea1nh\n| mother = L\u00ea Th\u1ecb O\u00e1nh\n| birth_date= 17 October 503\n| death_date = 13 April 548\n| place of burial = Vinh Tomb, [[Lam S\u01a1n (ancient Vietnam)|Lam S\u01a1n]]\n}}\n'''L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf''' ([[ch\u1eef H\u00e1n]]: \u674e\u5357\u5e1d, 17 October 503 \u2013 13 April 548) was a Vietnamese monarch and the founder of [[Name of Vietnam|V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n]]. ruling between 544-8 and the founder of the [[Early L\u00fd Dynasty]].<ref>{{cite book| title=Vietnam Country Map |publisher=Periplus Travel Maps |year=2002&ndash;03 |isbn=0-7946-0070-0}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\n\n'''L\u00fd B\u00f4n''' (\u674e\u8cc1) was descended from Chinese refugees who fled [[Wang Mang]]'s seizure of power during the interregnum between the Western and Eastern [[Han dynasty|Han dynasties]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=rCl_02LnNVIC&pg=PA135 Taylor (1983), p. 135]</ref><ref>Walker (2012), p. 134  {{Google books|GBvRs-za0CIC|East Asia: A New History|page=134}}</ref><ref>Catino (2010), p. 142  {{Google books|EL4wX0AFVJEC|The Aggressors: Ho Chi Minh, North Vietnam, and the Communist Bloc|page=142}}</ref><ref>Kohn (2006), p. 308  {{Google books|OIzreCGlHxIC|Dictionary of Wars|page=320}}</ref><ref>Coed\u00e8s (1966), pp. 45\u201346  {{Google books|qgrAFlAC4-QC|The Making of South East Asia|pages=45\u201346}}</ref><ref>Lockhart (2010), p. 221  {{Google books|NYu4JuWyhNcC|The A to Z of Vietnam|page=221}}</ref><ref>West (2009), p. 870  {{Google books|pCiNqFj3MQsC|Encyclopedia of the Peoples of Asia and Oceania|page=870}}</ref> He was a regional magistrate of Giao Ch\u00e2u (\u4ea4\u5dde, [[Chinese language|Chinese]]: Jiaozhou), an area of northern Vietnam roughly corresponding to the area of modern [[Hanoi]]. In 541, during this time China was under constant civil warfare following the [[Southern and Northern Dynasties]] Period, he became increasingly frustrated with the corruption in the government and hostility toward the local population. His friend-general [[Pham Tu]], was a ethnic [[Jie]], help him trained a initial army with 300 cavalry archers and started rebelling against the Liang dynasty. Upon resignation of his post he gathered the local nobility and locals within the [[Red River (Vietnam)|Red River]] Valley (North Vietnam) mobilized the imperial troops and naval fleet of Jiaozhou and successfully expelled the [[Liang Dynasty|Liang]] administration and won a decisive battle in Hofu in summer 543. The following year in February 544, L\u00fd B\u00ed was declared \"Emperor\" by the people with the intention of demonstrating equal in power to China imperial rulers. He renamed the new kingdom \"[[V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n]]\" ([[wikt:\u842c|\u842c]][[wikt:\u6625|\u6625]], literally \"Eternal Spring\"). His imperial armies also repelled attacks from [[Champa]] in the south who had allied with Han's court at the time.\n\n== Further in his life ==\n[[File:Map of V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n Kingdom during Early L\u00fd dynasty.png|left|thumb|220px|Map of V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n Kingdom ]]\nL\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf established his capital at Long Bi\u00ean (modern-day [[Hanoi]]), surrounded himself with effective leadership in military and administrative scholars. L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf was also strongly supported by famous military commander such as [[Ph\u1ea1m Tu]], [[Tri\u1ec7u T\u00fac]], [[Tinh Thi\u1ec1u]], and Tri\u1ec7u Quang Ph\u1ee5c, (son of Tri\u1ec7u Tuc, later known as [[Tri\u1ec7u Vi\u1ec7t V\u01b0\u01a1ng]]).  The latter emerged as a hero in Vietnamese history and eventually succeeded L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf as ruler in 548. L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf built many fortresses at strategic locations throughout V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n to fend off potential threats from Han in the north and from the Champa Kingdom in the south, he also established the first national university for mandarin scholars, implemented land reforms, and promoted literacy amongst the population.  He laid the foundation for many reforms that modelled after the Chinese social structure.\n\n[[File:Emperor Wu of Chen.jpg|222px|thumb|right|[[Emperor Wu of Chen|Tr\u1ea7n B\u00e1 Ti\u00ean]]]]\nStability of V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n did not last long and in October 544, the Liang Dynasty retaliated against V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n by sending 120,000 imperial troops to re-occupy the region.  The Liang emperor sent one of his generals [[Emperor Wu of Chen|Chen Baxian]] (Tr\u1ea7n B\u00e1 Ti\u00ean) and granted him sole command of the invading Liang forces.  By spring of 545, Chen had marched his army into V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n territory and laid [[siege]] and devastation to many cities.  His initial invasion was stalled by L\u00fd imperial forces for months.  However, in the winter of 545, Chen laid a surprised attack on the capital during the monsoon season.  L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf's imperial forces were caught off guard and the imperial administration was forced to abandon Long Bi\u00ean and flee westward into the neighboring kingdom of Laos.  The L\u00fd imperial forces were becoming weary and exhausted and L\u00fd himself was increasingly ill due to months of being exposed in the wilderness.  L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf realized that his illness would not enable him to rally the troops and accomplish a successful resistance against the imperial Chinese forces.  In February 548, he relinquished imperial authority and transferred his power to his older brother [[L\u00fd Thi\u00ean B\u1ea3o]] (co-ruler from 548 until his death in 555) and [[Tri\u1ec7u Vi\u1ec7t V\u01b0\u01a1ng|Tri\u1ec7u Quang Ph\u1ee5c]] (r. 548\u2013571), who was his best [[lieutenant]] and [[general]].\n\nBy April 548, after suffering from serious diseases for months, L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf died in [[Laos]] while fighting the Liang forces when local Laotian tribesmen assassinated him in hope for warding off the invading Liang army. His immediate successor was Tri\u1ec7u Quang Ph\u1ee5c (thereafter known as [[Tri\u1ec7u Vi\u1ec7t V\u01b0\u01a1ng]] which means Trieu Viet King).  The new king continued the resistance and eventually drove the Chinese out from V\u1ea1n Xu\u00e2n in 550.  Although China occupied Vietnam for approximately 1,000 years, L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf successfully established a Vi\u1ec7t dynasty that gave Northern Vietnam approximately 60 years of independence in between those times.\n\n==Anterior L\u00fd Dynasty==\n* L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf I (r. 542\u2013548)\n* [[L\u00fd Thi\u00ean B\u1ea3o]] (r. 548\u2013555, co-reigned with Tri\u1ec7u Quang Ph\u1ee5c)\n* [[Tri\u1ec7u Vi\u1ec7t V\u01b0\u01a1ng]] (r. 548\u2013571, 555\u2013571 as sole ruler)\n* [[Posterior Hau L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf|L\u00fd Nam \u0110\u1ebf II]] (r. 571\u2013602)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Taylor, Keith Weller. (1983). [https://books.google.com/books?id=rCl_02LnNVIC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false ''The Birth of Vietnam''] (illustrated, reprint ed.). University of California Press. {{ISBN|0520074173}}. Retrieved 7 August 2013.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|Early L\u00fd Dynasty|October 17,|503|April 13,|548}}\n{{s-bef|before=None}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Vietnamese monarchs|Emperor of Nam Vi\u1ec7t]]|years=544\u2013548}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Tri\u1ec7u Vi\u1ec7t V\u01b0\u01a1ng]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ly Nam De}}\n[[Category:Early L\u00fd Dynasty Kings]]\n[[Category:503 births]]\n[[Category:548 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "a > an", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L%C3%BD_Nam_%C4%90%E1%BA%BF"}
{"title_page": "History of the National University of San Marcos seal", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2007}}\n[[Image:UNMSM logo2.jpg|thumb|right|100px|The second logo improved the seal's round shape, modified the angel pattern and made clear its wings, among other modifications.]]\n[[Image:Unmsm-450anniversary.PNG|thumb|right|100px|The National University of San Marcos's 450th anniversary seal. The same elements were used for the third generation seal in early 2000; it added a [[red]] background and golden [[Picture frame|frame]] for the number ''450''.]]\n[[Image:Unmsm-early1500.PNG|thumb|100px|left|The 1574 version of the original University seal: [[Saint Mark]] writing at a desk, a [[lion]], three crowns, and the Latin phrase ''\"Plus ultra\"''.]] \n[[Image:Unmsm.png|thumb|right|100px|The third logo added light [[computer-generated imagery]] effects; the [[RGB color model]] was used and golden effects were added for seal's frame and shade in background.]]\n\nSince its founding in the 1550s, the [[National University of San Marcos]]' identifying symbols changed over the years, although the main [[pattern]] has been consistently maintained.\n\n==First logo==\nFrom its founding until 1574, the university's first official [[seal (device)|seal]] featured an [[icon]] of the ''\"Virgen del Rosario\"'' (''[[Virgin]] of the [[Rosary]]''), [[patron saint]] of the [[Dominican Order|Dominican]] [[friar]]s; at the right was a representation of the [[Pacific Ocean]] and on the bottom a [[lime (fruit)]] (that is, the fruit, which in [[Spanish language|Spanish]] is ''una lima'', hence Lima, Peru).\n\nThe logo was approved by [[monarch|King]] [[Charles I of Spain]] in 1551. By the late 1570s and after a [[papal bull]] of [[Pope Pius V]], the seal was modified, replacing the icon of ''Virgen del Rosario'' with [[Saint Mark]]. It is uncertain which colors were used on this seal, because documents in the 16th century were only [[black-and-white]] paper prints. It was not until 1929 when the colors&mdash;[[blue]] for the ocean, [[black]] or [[brown]] for the saint's icon, a [[light blue (color)|light blue]] background, and [[silver (color)|silver]] for [[columns]]&mdash;became popular.\n\nThis logo was the longest-enduring symbol of the university: it was used for almost four and a half centuries, until the late 1980s, when it was improved for the second generation logo.\n\n==Second logo==\nThe first logo was revised and lightly improved in the early 1990s, and it was fully improved on May 12, 1991, when university celebrated its 440th anniversary. Major changes were made to the angel's shape and its [[wing]]s, but the main pattern remained unchanged. This logo gained quickly popularity, hence it survived all the decade. This seal featured the same colors as were used since late 1920s, but the [[grayscale|black-and-white]] version is known by almost all graduate students of those days. This seal was improved for the third generation logo in early 2000s.\n\n==Third logo==\nThe third generation logo used today was released in early 2000s. It became official on May 12, 2001, when the university celebrated its 450th anniversary; at the same time a special logo was made for this year, which was used throughout 2001 and 2002. Since it was introduced in early 2000 this logo has been the university's official symbol, and is widely used on media advertisements.\n\n[[Category:History of education in Peru|National University of San Marcos seal]]\n[[Category:History of universities|National University of San Marcos seal]]\n[[Category:National University of San Marcos]]\n[[Category:Seals of organizations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2007}}\n[[Image:UNMSM logo2.jpg|thumb|right|100px|The second logo improved the seal's round shape, modified the angel pattern and made clear its wings, among other modifications.]]\n[[Image:Unmsm-450anniversary.PNG|thumb|right|100px|The National University of San Marcos's 450th anniversary seal. The same elements were used for the third generation seal in early 2000; it added a [[red]] background and golden [[Picture frame|frame]] for the number ''450''.]]\n[[Image:Unmsm-early1500.PNG|thumb|100px|left|The 1574 version of the original University seal: [[Saint Mark]] writing at a desk, a [[lion]], three crowns, and the Latin phrase ''\"Plus ultra\"''.]] \n[[Image:Unmsm.png|thumb|right|100px|The third logo added light [[computer-generated imagery]] effects; the [[RGB color model]] was used and golden effects were added for seal's frame and shade in background.]]\n\nSince its founding in the 1550s, the [[National University of San Marcos]]' identifying symbols changed over the years, although the main [[pattern]] has been consistently maintained.\n\n==First logo==\nFrom its founding until 1574, the university's first official [[seal (device)|seal]] featured an [[icon]] of the ''\"Virgen del Rosario\"'' (''[[Virgin]] of the [[Rosary]]''), [[patron saint]] of the [[Dominican Order|Dominican]] [[friar]]s; at the right was a representation of the [[Pacific Ocean]] and on the bottom a [[lime (fruit)]] (that is, the fruit, which in [[Spanish language|Spanish]] is ''una lima'', hence Lima, Peru).\n\nThe logo was approved by [[monarch|King]] [[Charles I of Spain]] in 1551. By the late 1570s and after a [[papal bull]] of [[Pope Pius V]], the seal was modified, replacing the icon of ''Virgen del Rosario'' with [[Saint Mark]]. It is uncertain which colors were used on this seal, because documents in the 16th century were only [[black-and-white]] paper prints. It wasn't until 1929 when the colors&mdash;[[blue]] for the ocean, [[black]] or [[brown]] for the saint's icon, a [[light blue (color)|light blue]] background, and [[silver]] for [[columns]]&mdash;became popular.\n\nThis logo was the longest-enduring symbol of the university: it was used for almost four and a half centuries, until the late 1980s, when it was improved for the second generation logo.\n\n==Second logo==\nThe first logo was revised and lightly improved in the early 1990s, and it was fully improved on May 12, 1991, when university celebrated its 440th anniversary. Major changes were made to the angel's shape and its [[wing]]s, but the main pattern remained unchanged. This logo gained quickly popularity, hence it survived all the decade. This seal featured the same colors as were used since late 1920s, but the [[grayscale|black-and-white]] version is known by almost all graduate students of those days. This seal was improved for the third generation logo in early 2000s.\n\n==Third logo==\nThe third generation logo used today was released in early 2000s. It became official on May 12, 2001, when the university celebrated its 450th anniversary; at the same time a special logo was made for this year, which was used throughout 2001 and 2002. Since it was introduced in early 2000 this logo has been the university's official symbol, and is widely used on media advertisements.\n\n[[Category:History of education in Peru|National University of San Marcos seal]]\n[[Category:History of universities|National University of San Marcos seal]]\n[[Category:National University of San Marcos]]\n[[Category:Seals of organizations]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFirst logo:clean up, replaced:silver\u2192silver", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_National_University_of_San_Marcos_seal"}
{"title_page": "Iran\u2013Iraq border", "text_new": "[[File:Tigr-euph.png|thumb|right|220px|Iran\u2013Iraq border runs through the Tigris watershed (above), leaving the river in Iraqi hands.]]\n{{Refimprove|date=March 2017}}\nThe '''[[Iran]]\u2013[[Iraq]] border''' runs for 1,599 km (994 m) from the [[tripoint]] with [[Turkey]] in the north down to to the [[Shatt al-Arab]] (known as Arvand Rud in Iran) waterway and out to the [[Persian Gulf]] in the south.<ref>{{cite |url= https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/iz.html|title=CIA World Factbook - Iraq|accessdate= 4 April 2020</ref> Although the boundary was first determined in 1639, certain disputes continue, particularly surrounding navigation on the Shatt al-Arab.\n\n==Boundary line==\nThe boundary starts in the [[Persian Gulf]] at the \"lowest point of low water\" at the mouth of the [[Shatt al-Arab]] at {{coord|29|51|16|N|48|44|45|E}} ([[WGS84]].) It then closely follows the [[thalweg]] of the Shatt al-Arab for some 105.2 km in a series of short straight line segments, reaching the confluence of the Shatt al-Arab and the Nahr al-Khayin tributary. From there, it winds northward, following a series of boundary markers across plain and hill, through the [[Zagros Mountains]] Nahr at-Tib, and Nahr Wadi. It meets the boundary with Turkey at 37\u00b0 08' 44\" N and 44\u00b0 47' 05\" E.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Shatt al arab.png|thumb|left|240px|The boundary line in the Shatt al-Arab waterway is still disputed between Iran and Iraq.]]\nThe boundary dates back to the [[Treaty of Zuhab|1639 Zuhab Treaty]] between [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Turkey]] and [[Safavid Empire|Safavid Iran]], which left the former in decisive control of what is present-day Iraq.{{sfn|Kia|2017|page=46}} The agreement stipulated that the boundary would run between the Zagros Mountains and the [[Tigris River]]. In 1724, the Ottomans rejected the boundary-line and invaded Iran, but when peace was finally concluded in 1746, the two states recognized the 1639 boundary as official. That was affirmed by the [[Treaties of Erzurum#Second Treaty|1847 Treaty of Erzurum]], but the new treaty first raised the issue of the [[Shatt al-Arab]] waterway. The boundary was set at the eastern bank of the Persian gulf so that the entire waterway remained under Turkish ([[Iraq]]i) control. In the following years, the boundary-line was further delineated, and a detailed [[map]] was produced in 1860.\n\n[[File:Iran-Iraq border 04.jpg|thumb|Iran-Iraq border in 2015]]\nA more precise demarcation was begun in 1911 at the urging of [[Russian Empire|Russia]] and the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Britain]], both of whom had [[colonialism|colonial]] aspirations in the region.\n\nIn 1913 and 1914, a commission established by the Constantinople Protocol set the revised boundary, with control of the Shatt al-Arab going to Turkey. In general, the line was to follow the east bank of the waterway except in the region surrounding the Iranian town of [[Khorramshahr]], where it was to follow the thalweg.\n\nThat was challenged by [[Imperial State of Iran|Iran]] in 1934, as the validity of both the Treaty of Erzurum and the Istanbul Protocol was called into question. The dispute was resolved in 1937, following the general lines of the old boundary, with the exception of the area immediately around the Iranian town of [[Abadan, Iran|Abadan]], where the boundary was moved from the east bank to the thalweg, as had been done around Khorramshahr two decades earlier.\n\nWhile that resolved Iran's major grievances, it failed to respond to the issue of freedom of navigation in the Shatt al-Arab. Iraq finally accepted the new boundary in 1991, during the occupation of [[Kuwait]], in accordance with [[United Nations]] [[s:United Nations Security Council Resolution 598|Resolution 598]].\n\n==Border crossings==\nBorder crossings are [[Shalamja]], [[Mundhiriya]], [[al-Shib]], [[Zarbatiya]], and [[Mandali Soomar]]. Additionally the [[Kurdistan Region]] has four international border crossing between Kurdistan and Iran at [[Haji Omaran]] (in [[Erbil Province]]), [[Parwezkhan]], [[Bashmaq, Marivan|Bashmaq]], and (from 2016) at Sayran Ban located in the town of Penjwen in [[Sulaymaniyah Governorate]].\n\nParwiz border point ({{lang-fa|\u06af\u0630\u0631\u06af\u0627\u0647 \u0645\u0631\u0632\u06cc \u067e\u0631\u0648\u06cc\u0632\u062e\u0627\u0646}}) is the name of the main border trade center in the west of [[Iran]]. It was announced as an official international border control point on December 31, 2007. It is located north of the city of [[Qasr-e Shirin]] in [[Kermanshah province]] of Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.is/20130218070811/http://edition.presstv.ir/detail/36964.html|title=Parviz Khan border point official|website=Archive.is|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Al-Fakkah Field]] dispute\n* [[Haji Homaran]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Biger, Gideon. ''The Encyclopedia of International Boundaries'', Facts on File, 1995. {{ISBN|0-8160-3233-5}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Kia|first1=Mehrdad|title=The Ottoman Empire: A Historical Encyclopedia|date=2017|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1610693899|page=46|ref=harv}}\n\n{{Borders of Iraq}}\n{{Borders of Iran}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iran-Iraq border}}\n[[Category:Iran\u2013Iraq border|*]]\n[[Category:Borders of Iran]]\n[[Category:Borders of Iraq]]\n[[Category:International borders]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Tigr-euph.png|thumb|right|220px|Iran\u2013Iraq border runs through the Tigris watershed (above), leaving the river in Iraqi hands.]]\n{{Refimprove|date=March 2017}}\nThe '''[[Iran]]\u2013[[Iraq]] border''' runs for 1,599 km (994 m) from the [[tripoint]] with [[Turkey]] in the north at the [[Kuh e-Dalanper]] down to to the [[Shatt al-Arab]] (known as Arvand Rud in Iran) waterway and out to the [[Persian Gulf]] in the south..<ref>{{cite |url= https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/iz.html|title=CIA World Factbook - Iraq|accessdate= 4 April 2020</ref> Although the boundary was first determined in 1639, certain disputes continue, particularly surrounding navigation on the Shatt al-Arab.\n\n==Boundary line==\nThe boundary starts in the [[Persian Gulf]] at the \"lowest point of low water\" at the mouth of the [[Shatt al-Arab]] at {{coord|29|51|16|N|48|44|45|E}} ([[WGS84]].) It then closely follows the [[thalweg]] of the Shatt al-Arab for some 105.2 km in a series of short straight line segments, reaching the confluence of the Shatt al-Arab and the Nahr al-Khayin tributary. From there, it winds northward, following a series of boundary markers across plain and hill, through the [[Zagros Mountains]] Nahr at-Tib, and Nahr Wadi. It meets the boundary with Turkey at 37\u00b0 08' 44\" N and 44\u00b0 47' 05\" E.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Shatt al arab.png|thumb|left|240px|The boundary line in the Shatt al-Arab waterway is still disputed between Iran and Iraq.]]\nThe boundary dates back to the [[Treaty of Zuhab|1639 Zuhab Treaty]] between [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Turkey]] and [[Safavid Empire|Safavid Iran]], which left the former in decisive control of what is present-day Iraq.{{sfn|Kia|2017|page=46}} The agreement stipulated that the boundary would run between the Zagros Mountains and the [[Tigris River]]. In 1724, the Ottomans rejected the boundary-line and invaded Iran, but when peace was finally concluded in 1746, the two states recognized the 1639 boundary as official. That was affirmed by the [[Treaties of Erzurum#Second Treaty|1847 Treaty of Erzurum]], but the new treaty first raised the issue of the [[Shatt al-Arab]] waterway. The boundary was set at the eastern bank of the Persian gulf so that the entire waterway remained under Turkish ([[Iraq]]i) control. In the following years, the boundary-line was further delineated, and a detailed [[map]] was produced in 1860.\n\n[[File:Iran-Iraq border 04.jpg|thumb|Iran-Iraq border in 2015]]\nA more precise demarcation was begun in 1911 at the urging of [[Russian Empire|Russia]] and the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Britain]], both of whom had [[colonialism|colonial]] aspirations in the region.\n\nIn 1913 and 1914, a commission established by the Constantinople Protocol set the revised boundary, with control of the Shatt al-Arab going to Turkey. In general, the line was to follow the east bank of the waterway except in the region surrounding the Iranian town of [[Khorramshahr]], where it was to follow the thalweg.\n\nThat was challenged by [[Imperial State of Iran|Iran]] in 1934, as the validity of both the Treaty of Erzurum and the Istanbul Protocol was called into question. The dispute was resolved in 1937, following the general lines of the old boundary, with the exception of the area immediately around the Iranian town of [[Abadan, Iran|Abadan]], where the boundary was moved from the east bank to the thalweg, as had been done around Khorramshahr two decades earlier.\n\nWhile that resolved Iran's major grievances, it failed to respond to the issue of freedom of navigation in the Shatt al-Arab. Iraq finally accepted the new boundary in 1991, during the occupation of [[Kuwait]], in accordance with [[United Nations]] [[s:United Nations Security Council Resolution 598|Resolution 598]].\n\n==Border crossings==\nBorder crossings are [[Shalamja]], [[Mundhiriya]], [[al-Shib]], [[Zarbatiya]], and [[Mandali Soomar]]. Additionally the [[Kurdistan Region]] has four international border crossing between Kurdistan and Iran at [[Haji Omaran]] (in [[Erbil Province]]), [[Parwezkhan]], [[Bashmaq, Marivan|Bashmaq]], and (from 2016) at Sayran Ban located in the town of Penjwen in [[Sulaymaniyah Governorate]].\n\nParwiz border point ({{lang-fa|\u06af\u0630\u0631\u06af\u0627\u0647 \u0645\u0631\u0632\u06cc \u067e\u0631\u0648\u06cc\u0632\u062e\u0627\u0646}}) is the name of the main border trade center in the west of [[Iran]]. It was announced as an official international border control point on December 31, 2007. It is located north of the city of [[Qasr-e Shirin]] in [[Kermanshah province]] of Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.is/20130218070811/http://edition.presstv.ir/detail/36964.html|title=Parviz Khan border point official|website=Archive.is|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Al-Fakkah Field]] dispute\n* [[Haji Homaran]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Biger, Gideon. ''The Encyclopedia of International Boundaries'', Facts on File, 1995. {{ISBN|0-8160-3233-5}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Kia|first1=Mehrdad|title=The Ottoman Empire: A Historical Encyclopedia|date=2017|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1610693899|page=46|ref=harv}}\n\n{{Borders of Iraq}}\n{{Borders of Iran}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iran-Iraq border}}\n[[Category:Iran\u2013Iraq border|*]]\n[[Category:Borders of Iran]]\n[[Category:Borders of Iraq]]\n[[Category:International borders]]\n", "name_user": "WisDom-UK", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iran%E2%80%93Iraq_border"}
{"title_page": "Cleo Walker", "text_new": "{{short description|American football center and linebacker}}\n'''Cleo Walker''' is a former [[linebacker]] and [[Center (American football)|center]] in the [[National Football League]].\n\n==Biography==\nWalker was born Cleo Franklin Walker on February 7th 1948 in [[Columbus, Georgia]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/W/WalkCl20.htm |title = Cleo Walker Stats}}</ref>\nCleo Walker writes this note to me about himself. [\" In the last pre season game of the 1970 season Green Bay Vs Oakland @ Oakland. Then rookie Cleo Walker  intercepted Kenny [ The Snake ] Stabler three times in the 4th Qtr. these steals not only sealed  the game for Green Bay , but also assured Walker a place on the Green Bay Packers roster.\" ]   Cleo Walker 2016 .\n\n==Career==\nWalker was drafted by the [[Green Bay Packers]] in the seventh round of the [[1970 NFL Draft]] and played that season with the team. The following season, he played with the [[Atlanta Falcons]].\n\nHe played at the collegiate level at the [[University of Louisville]].<ref>{{Cite web |   url=http://www.nfl.com/players/cleowalker/profile?id=WAL111804 |title = Cleo Walker}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Green Bay Packers players]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Packers1970DraftPicks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walker, Cleo}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Columbus, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Falcons players]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:American football centers]]\n[[Category:Louisville Cardinals football players]]\n\n\n{{ULouisville-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Cleo Walker''' is a former [[linebacker]] and [[Center (American football)|center]] in the [[National Football League]].\n\n==Biography==\nWalker was born Cleo Franklin Walker on February 7th 1948 in [[Columbus, Georgia]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.pro-football-re