dium]].}} ([[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|FBS]]) ||  Houston, TX<ref>[http://www.erugbynews.com/article.php?sec=143&a=4901 \"Not a New Dawn, But Nice Anyway\"], ERugbyNews,  June 1, 2009.</ref>\n|-\n| 11 || '''14,000''' || New Zealand XV || 1980-10-08 || [[SDCCU Stadium|San Diego Stadium]]{{efn|group=att|Now known as SDCCU Stadium.}} (NFL) ||  San Diego, CA\n|-\n| 12 || '''13,591''' || Chile || 2016-02-20 || [[Lockhart Stadium]]{{efn|group=att|Demolished in 2019 and replaced on-site by [[Inter Miami CF Stadium]].}} (NASL) || Fort Lauderdale, FL\n|-\n| 13 || '''11,300''' || Scotland || 2018-06-16 || [[BBVA Stadium|BBVA Compass Stadium]]{{efn|group=att|name=BBVA}} (MLS) || Houston, TX\n|-\n| 14 || '''11,000''' || Japan || 2015-07-24 || [[Papa Murphy's Park|Bonney Field]]{{efn|group=att|Now known as Papa Murphy's Park.}} (USL) || Sacramento, CA\n|-\n| 15 || '''10,241''' || [[Argentina XV national rugby union team|Argentina XV]] || 2016-02-06 || [[BBVA Stadium|BBVA Compass Stadium]]{{efn|group=att|name=BBVA}} (MLS) || Houston, TX\n|}\n\n;Notes\n{{notelist|group=att}}\n*The international rugby match in the U.S. with the largest crowd did not involve the United States national team; 62,000 watched Ireland defeat New Zealand 40\u201329 at Soldier Field on November 5, 2016.<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/sport/rugby/live-coverage-of-all-blacks-v-ireland-from-chicagos-soldier-field/news-story/46521ddbc332bb1fa18da359b04fa027 \"Inspired Ireland record first ever win over All Blacks at Chicago\u2019s Soldier Field\"], News.com.au, November 6, 2016.</ref>\n\n==Rivalry with Canada ==\n{{main|History of rugby union matches between Canada and United States}}\n\nThe United States' biggest rival in rugby is [[Canada national rugby union team|Canada]].  The US has played more test matches against Canada than any other country.  The two teams first met in 1977, and have played every year since then with the exception of 2010.  As of the end of 2019, the two sides have met 58 times, with 22 wins for the U.S., 38 wins for Canada, and 2 draws.\n\nThe U.S. and Canada routinely play each other in qualifying matches for the Rugby World Cup.  They have met in the qualification stages for every tournament, except for the 1987 tournament, for which teams were invited rather than going through qualification matches, and the 1995 tournament, for which Canada had automatically qualified by finishing as a quarterfinalist in the 1991 Rugby World Cup. Since 2015, the teams play each other annually at the [[Americas Rugby Championship]].\n\nThe U.S. has been undefeated in the last 12 matches, with 11 wins and a draw. The first victory of the Eagles' current unbeaten streak ended a seven-match winning streak by Canada that lasted from 2009 through 2013.\n\n==Tournament records==\n===Honors===\n*[[2018 Americas Rugby Championship]] \u2013 Champion\n*[[2017 Americas Rugby Championship]] \u2013 Champion\n*[[Rugby union at the 1924 Summer Olympics|1924 Olympics]] \u2013 Gold Medal\n*[[Rugby union at the 1920 Summer Olympics|1920 Olympics]] \u2013 Gold Medal\n\n===Rugby World Cup===\n{{main|United States at the Rugby World Cup}}\nThe United States has qualified for every [[Rugby World Cup]] except the 1995 tournament. The best result that the U.S. has managed at a Rugby World Cup is to win one game, which it accomplished in 1987, 2003, and again in 2011.\n\n{|class = \"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Tournament\n!Host\n!U.S. Win/Loss <br /> (Bonus Pts){{refn|group=o|A bonus point is awarded for scoring 4 tries or for losing by 7 points or less.}} \n!U.S. Finish\n! U.S. Defeated\n! Leading U.S. scorer\n|-\n| [[1987 Rugby World Cup|1987]]\n| align=left | {{Ru|AUS}}<br />{{Ru|NZL}}\n|1\u20132\n|3rd in Pool A\n| Japan (21\u201318)\n| [[Ray Nelson (rugby union)|Ray Nelson]] (24)\n|-\n| [[1991 Rugby World Cup|1991]]\n| align=left | {{ru|ENG}}<br />{{ru|FRA}}<br />{{ru|IRE}}<br />{{ru|SCO}}<br />{{ru|WAL}} \n|0\u20133\n|4th in Pool A\n| \u2014\n| [[Mark Williams (rugby player)|Mark Williams]] (16)\n|-\n| [[1995 Rugby World Cup|1995]]\n| align=left | {{Ru|RSA}}\n| colspan=4 | ''[[1995 Rugby World Cup \u2013 Americas qualification|Did not qualify]]''\n|-\n| [[1999 Rugby World Cup|1999]]\n| align=left | {{Ru|WAL}}\n|0\u20133\n|4th in Pool 5\n| \u2014\n| [[Kevin Dalzell]] (22)\n|-\n| [[2003 Rugby World Cup|2003]]\n| align=left | {{Ru|AUS}}\n|1\u20133 (2 BP)\n|4th in Pool B\n| Japan (39\u201326)\n| [[Mike Hercus]] (51)\n|-\n| [[2007 Rugby World Cup|2007]]\n| align=left | {{Ru|FRA}}\n|0\u20134 (1 BP)\n|5th in Pool A\n| \u2014\n| [[Mike Hercus]] (26)\n|-\n| [[2011 Rugby World Cup|2011]]\n| align=left | {{Ru|NZL}}\n|1\u20133 (0 BP)\n|4th in Pool C\n| Russia (13\u20136)\n| [[Chris Wyles]] (18)\n|-\n| [[2015 Rugby World Cup|2015]]\n| align=left | {{Ru|ENG}}\n| 0\u20134 (0 BP)\n| 5th in Pool B\n| \u2014\n| [[AJ MacGinty]] (25)\n|-\n| [[2019 Rugby World Cup|2019]]\n| align=left | {{Ru|JPN}}\n| 0\u20134 (0 BP)\n|5th in Pool C\n| \u2014\n| [[AJ MacGinty]] (17)\n|-\n|}\n\n{{reflist|group=o}}\n\n===Pacific Nations Cup===\n{{Main|World Rugby Pacific Nations Cup}}\n\nThe Pacific Nations Cup has been played every year since 2006, and has been played in its current format since 2013, when the United States and Canada joined Japan, Fiji, Samoa and Tonga. \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! Tournament !! U.S. record !! U.S. finish !! Leading U.S. scorer !! U.S. wins\n|-\n| [[2013 IRB Pacific Nations Cup|2013]] || 0\u20134 || 5th / 5 || [[Chris Wyles]] (19) || \u2014\n|-\n| [[2014 IRB Pacific Nations Cup|2014]] || 1\u20131 || 3rd / 6 || [[Chris Wyles]] (32) || Canada \n|-\n| [[2015 World Rugby Pacific Nations Cup|2015]] || 2\u20132 || 5th / 6 || [[AJ MacGinty]] (44) || Japan, Canada \n|-\n| [[2019 World Rugby Pacific Nations Cup|2019]] || 2\u20131 || 3rd / 6  || [[AJ MacGinty]] (28) ||  Canada, Samoa\n|-\n|}\n\n===Americas Rugby Championship===\n{{Main|Americas Rugby Cup}}\n\nThe Americas Rugby Championship pits the six highest ranked rugby nations in North and South America (Argentina XV, Brazil, Canada, Chile, United States, and Uruguay). It was first contested in 2016. \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! Tournament !! U.S. record !! U.S. finish !! Leading U.S. scorer !! U.S. wins\n|-\n| [[2016 Americas Rugby Championship|2016]] || 2\u20131-2 || 2nd || [[James Bird (rugby union)|James Bird]] (32) || Canada, Chile \n|-\n| [[2017 Americas Rugby Championship|2017]] || 4\u20131-0 || 1st || [[Ben Cima]] (36) || Uruguay, Brazil, Canada, Chile \n|-\n| [[2018 Americas Rugby Championship|2018]] || 5\u20130-0 || 1st || [[Will Magie]] (38) || Argentina XV, Uruguay, Brazil, Canada, Chile \n|-\n| [[2019 Americas Rugby Championship|2019]] || 3\u20130-2 || 3rd || [[Joe Taufete'e]] (30) || Brazil, Canada, Chile \n|-\n|}\n\n===Summer Olympics===\n{{main|Rugby union at the Summer Olympics}}\nRugby was included an Olympic sport four times from 1900 to 1924, with the United States winning the last two of those tournaments \u2014 1920 and 1924. After a lengthy absence, rugby returned to the Summer Olympics in 2016, albeit in the [[rugby sevens]] format.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Olympics !! U.S. finish !! U.S. record !! Defeated\n|-\n| align=left | {{flagicon|FRA|1794}} [[Rugby union at the 1900 Summer Olympics|1900 Paris]]\n| colspan=3|''(U.S. did not participate)''\n|-\n| align=left | {{flagicon|UK|1801|size=23px}} [[Rugby union at the 1908 Summer Olympics|1908 London]]\n| colspan=3|''(U.S. did not participate)''\n|-\n| align=left | {{flagicon|BEL}} [[Rugby union at the 1920 Summer Olympics|1920 Antwerp]]\n| bgcolor=gold | '''Gold'''\n| 1\u20130\n| France\n|-\n| align=left | {{flagicon|FRA|1794}} [[Rugby union at the 1924 Summer Olympics|1924 Paris]]\n| bgcolor=gold | '''Gold'''\n| 2\u20130\n| France, Romania\n|-\n|}\n\n===Defunct competitions===\n====Churchill Cup====\n{{Main|Churchill Cup