cas Rugby Championship|2010]]\n| [[Argentina Jaguars]]\n|3rd  \n|-\n| 2011\n| colspan=3 | ''Not held due to the [[2011 Rugby World Cup]]''\n|-\n|[[2012 Americas Rugby Championship|2012]]\n| [[Argentina Jaguars]]\n|4th  \n|- style=\"background: #efefef;\"\n|[[2013 Americas Rugby Championship|2013]]\n| [[Argentina Jaguars]]\n|2nd  \n|-\n|[[2014 Americas Rugby Championship|2014]]\n| [[Argentina Jaguars]]\n|2nd  \n|-\n| 2015\n| colspan=3 | ''Not held due to the [[2015 Rugby World Cup]]''\n|-\n|}\n{{Main|USA Selects}}\n{{Update|section|date=January 2019}}\n\nThe USA Selects is a second national rugby team for the United States. The USA Selects is a developmental team, usually fielding younger players looking to break into the U.S. national team, and sometimes including amateur domestic U.S. national team players who need more high-level matches.\n\nThe USA Selects participates in the [[Americas Rugby Championship]], a tournament featuring the \"A\" sides for Argentina, Canada, the United States, and Uruguay. The ARC is an annual tournament that has been played every year since 2009 (except for Rugby World Cup years), and replaces the North America 4 competition. The USA Selects best result in the ARC was in 2013, when the USA Selects beat Canada A to take second place.<ref>[http://usarugby.org/mens-eagles-news/item/eagles-select-xvs-defeat-canada-30-10-at-americas-rugby-championship \"Eagles Select XVs defeat Canada 30-10 at Americas Rugby Championship\"], USA Rugby, October 15, 2013. Retrieved September 13, 2014.</ref>\n\n===Women's national team===\n{{Main|United States women's national rugby union team}}\nThe U.S. women's national team, officially formed in 1987, has been an international powerhouse since its inception, although more recently have fallen behind other powerhouses such as England and New Zealand on the [[Women's international rugby union#Women.27s Test Ranking|world rankings]]. The Eagles won the first official World Cup in 1991, and finished second in the two following World Cups (1994, 1998). The Eagles have set a high standard for international competition, leading an ensuing wave of women's rugby growth and game development worldwide.  The US finished 7th in the 2002 tournament.  The women's national team traveled to the United Kingdom in January 2006 to play Scotland, Ireland and England, winning all three games. The 2006 Women's Rugby World Cup was held in Edmonton, Canada.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n* [[Rugby union in the United States]]\n* [[USA Rugby]]\n* [[United States national rugby sevens team]]\n* [[United States national under-20 rugby union team]]\n* [[List of United States national rugby union players]]\n* [[Rugby World Cup]]\n* [[American Cougars]]\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|United States national rugby union team}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.usarugby.org/}}\n\n{{United States national rugby union team}}\n{{Rugby union in the United States}}\n{{USNationalTeams}}\n{{National rugby teams}}\n{{Churchill Cup}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:United States National Rugby Union Team}}\n[[Category:North American national rugby union teams]]\n[[Category:United States national rugby union team| ]]\n[[Category:National sports teams of the United States|Rugby union]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|United States national rugby sevens team}}\n{{About|the men's team|the women's team|United States women's national rugby union team}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox national rugby team\n| Name                  = United States of America\n| Nickname              = ''Eagles''\n| Badge                 = \n| Badge_size            = 200px\n| Emblem                = [[Bald eagle|American bald eagle]]\n| Union                 = [[USA Rugby]]\n| Coach                 = [[Gary Gold]]\n| Captain               = [[Blaine Scully]]\n| Most caps             = [[Todd Clever]] (76)\n| Top scorer            = [[Mike Hercus]] (465)\n| Top try scorer        = [[Vaea Anitoni]] (26)\n| pattern_la1           = _usarugby19h\n| pattern_b1            = _usarugby19h\n| pattern_ra1           = _usarugby19h\n| pattern_sh1           = _navysides\n| pattern_so1           =  \n| leftarm1              = ffffff\n| body1                 = ffffff\n| rightarm1             = ffffff\n| shorts1               = ffffff\n| socks1                = ffffff\n| pattern_la2           = _usarugby19a \n| pattern_b2            = _usarugby19a\n| pattern_ra2           = _usarugby19a\n| pattern_sh2           = _whitesides \n| pattern_so2           =  \n| leftarm2              = 003052 \n| body2                 = 003052 \n| rightarm2             = 003052 \n| shorts2               = 003052  \n| socks2                = 003052 \n| American              = true\n| World Rugby Rank      = 16\n| World Rugby Rank date = March 26th, 2020\n| World Rugby max       = 13\n| World Rugby max year  = 2019\n| World Rugby min       = 20\n| World Rugby min year  = 2008\n| First game            = {{flagdeco|USA}} '''United States''' 8\u201312 [[Australia national rugby union team|Australia]] {{flagdeco|AUS}} <br />([[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]], [[California (state)|California]], U.S.; November 16, 1912)\n| Largest win           = {{flagdeco|USA}} '''United States''' 91\u20130 [[Barbados national rugby union team|Barbados]] {{flagdeco|BAR}} <br />([[Stanford, California|Stanford]], [[California (state)|California]], U.S.; July 1, 2006)\n| Largest loss          = {{flagdeco|ENG}} [[England national rugby union team|England]] 106\u20138 '''United States''' {{flagdeco|USA}} <br />([[London]], England; August 21, 1999)\n| World cup apps        = 8\n| World cup first       = 1987\n| World cup best        = Pool stage, [[1987 Rugby World Cup|1987]], [[1991 Rugby World Cup|1991]], [[1999 Rugby World Cup|1999]], [[2003 Rugby World Cup|2003]], [[2007 Rugby World Cup|2007]], [[2011 Rugby World Cup|2011]], [[2015 Rugby World Cup|2015]], and [[2019 Rugby World Cup|2019]]\n| medaltemplates        = {{MedalTop|}}\n{{MedalSport |Men's [[Rugby union at the Summer Olympics|rugby]]}}\n{{MedalGold |[[Rugby union at the 1920 Summer Olympics|1920 Antwerp]] | [[Rugby union at the 1920 Summer Olympics#Medalists|Team]]}}\n{{MedalGold |[[Rugby union at the 1924 Summer Olympics|1924 Paris]] | [[Rugby union at the 1924 Summer Olympics#Medalists|Team]]}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n|website = [https://www.usarugby.org/ www.usarugby.org]\n}}\n\nThe '''United States men's national rugby union team''', represents [[United States of America]] in men's international [[rugby union]], nicknamed the '''Eagles''' it's controlled by [[USA Rugby]]. USA Rugby is a member of [[Rugby Americas North]], one of six regional governing bodies under [[World Rugby]]. Until rugby returned to Olympic competition, with [[Rugby sevens|sevens]] at the [[Rugby sevens at the 2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Rio Games]], the United States was the reigning Olympic rugby champion, having defeated the one other competitor in [[Rugby union at the 1920 Summer Olympics|1920]] and the two other competitors at the [[Rugby union at the 1924 Summer Olympics|1924]] [[Rugby union at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]].\n\n{{As of|2019|October}}, the men's Eagles are ranked 17th in the world by the [[World Rugby Rankings]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldrugby.org/rankings|title=World Rugby |publisher=|access-date=October 14, 2019}}</ref> Their previous highest ranking, achieved ahead of the [[2019 Rugby World Cup|2019 World Cup]], was 13th; their lowest ranking was 20th, following a winless campaign in the [[2008 Churchill Cup]].\n\nThe highest profile tournament in which the men's Eagles play is the [[Rugby World Cup]]. The men's Eagles have played in all but one Rugby World Cup since the tournament began in 1987. The United States has expressed interest in hosting the 2027 Rugby World Cup.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2011/dec/01/united-states-bid-2023-rugby-world-cup \"United States ready to launch bid to host 2023 Rugby World Cup\"], ''The Guardian'', December 1, 2011.</ref>\n\nThe United States competed in the [[World Rugby Pacific Nations Cup|Pacific Nations Cup]] every Summer from 2013 to 2015. Previously, the U.S. has competed in the now-defunct [[Churchill Cup]] and the Pan American Championship.<ref>[http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/rugby/international/8214395/Canada-and-USA-to-join-Pacific-Nations-Cup \"Canada and USA to join Pacific Nations Cup\"], Stuff.co.nz, January 23, 2013. Retrieved April 10, 2015.</ref> In April 2015, USA Rugby announced the creation of a new, annual International Championship to be contested among the top-6 ranked rugby nations in the Americas: Argentina, Brazil, Canada, Chile, Uruguay and the United States. The contest was named the [[Americas Rugby Championship]] and began in [[2016 Americas Rugby Championship|2016]].<ref>[http://usarugby.org/mens-eagles-news/item/top-six-rugby-nation-championship \"Americas' top Six Rugby Nations Planning for Bright Future\"], Nick Sero, April 24, 2015.</ref> The United States won the [[2017 Americas Rugby Championship]] after drawing with [[Argentina XV national rugby union team|Argentina XV]]. It was the United States' first 15-a-side rugby union title in over 90 years. \n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Early history==\n{{See also|Rugby union in the United States#Early history}}\n\n===Early years: 1872\u20131912===\n[[File:McGill v harvard football game 1874.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The Harvard\u2013McGill game of 1874]]\nInformal football games such as rugby became popular in the United States in the mid-19th century. Rugby union was played as early as 1872 among rugby clubs in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] composed mainly of British expatriates. On December 2, 1882, the first [[California Golden Bears|Californian representative rugby team]] to play an outside opponent, took on a group of rugby-playing ex-Britons, who called themselves the Phoenix Rugby Club of San Francisco. California lost to the Phoenix club 7\u20134.\n\n[[File:Usa rugby team v australia.jpg|thumb|left|The USA side that played [[Australia national rugby union team|Australia]] at [[California Field]] during the ''Wallabies'' [[1912 Australia rugby union tour of Canada and the U.S.|1912 tour of Canada and the U.S.]]]]\n[[1874 Harvard vs. McGill football game|The first recorded rugby game in the U.S.]] was played in May 1874 when local [[Harvard Crimson|Harvard University]] hosted [[Canada|Canadian]] [[McGill Redmen and Martlets|McGill University]].<ref>[http://www.rugbyfootballhistory.com/USA.html Rugby in USA], Rugby Football History. Accessed September 26, 2015.</ref> The game sparked an interest on college campuses nationwide. In 1876 Yale, Harvard, [[Princeton University|Princeton]], and [[Columbia University|Columbia]] formed the Intercollegiate Football Association, which largely used the rugby code.<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/sports/gridiron-football Gridiron football], ''Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica''. Retrieved September 26, 2015.</ref> In 1886 Harvard's Oscar Shafter Howard introduced these rules to the campus of the [[University of California, Berkeley]].\n\n[[American football]] was fierce, and as injuries mounted, the public became alarmed at its brutalities and President Theodore Roosevelt threatened to outlaw the sport.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2012/02/05/opinion/greene-super-bowl/ \"The president who saved football\"], CNN, February 5, 2012. Retrieved September 26, 2015.</ref> Beginning in 1906, rugby union became the game of choice at [[Stanford University]], [[University of California, Berkeley]] and several other colleges in California.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/sep/25/rugby-america-college-university-world-cup \"Can American rugby move beyond the college campus?\"], ''The Guardian'', September 25, 2015.</ref> Rugby's popularity, however, was short lived, and the sport had died out by the outbreak of World War I.\n\nA California student team toured Australia and New Zealand in 1910, and invited their hosts to return the visit.<ref name=\"auto\">[http://en.espn.co.uk/newzealand/rugby/story/204045.html \"The tour that killed American rugby\"], ESPN Scrum, Huw Richards, October 29, 2013.</ref> Australia obliged by touring North America in 1912, and the U.S. national team played [[1912 Australia rugby union tour of Canada and the USA|its first international match]] on November 16, 1912 against [[Australia national rugby union team|Australia]] in Berkeley, California. The visitors won 12\u20138.<ref>[http://therugbyhistorysociety.co.uk/morris.html The Rugby History Society]. Retrieved March 25, 2015.</ref> A year later, the U.S. hosted [[New Zealand national rugby union team|New Zealand]] at the same venue on November 15, 1913, but the Kiwis ran away with the contest 51\u20133.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Olympic Gold: 1920 and 1924===\n[[File:USA rugby team for the october 1920 test match vs France.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The U.S. rugby team for the October 1920 test match vs France]]\nRugby union had not been played competitively in most of the U.S. for more than a decade before the [[Rugby union at the 1920 Summer Olympics|1920 Olympics]]. The U.S. Olympic committee decided that because \"California is the only state playing Rugby in the US, the Committee will give sanction but no financial aid\". The U.S. assembled mostly a California-based team, with six players from the [[California Golden Bears|University of California, Berkeley]].<ref name=\"californiagoldenblogs.com\">[http://www.californiagoldenblogs.com/2012/6/20/3067036/1924-rugby-a-wild-olympic-rematch \"1924 Rugby: A Wild Olympic Rematch\"], California Golden Blogs, June 20, 2012.</ref> The Olympic Games Committee of the [[Amateur Athletic Union]] paid the expenses to transport the team from California to the games in Antwerp.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=A.A.U. to Pay Expenses of Rugby Team to Olympics |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/20460636 |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=[[Stanford University]], [[California|Calif.]] |date=June 4, 1920 |via=[[Newspapers.com]] |access-date=October 8, 2018}}</ref> By the time the US Rugby team arrived in Europe, Czechoslovakia and Romania had withdrawn from the competition. [[France national rugby union team|France]] and the U.S. were the only teams left to compete. The U.S. won a shock 8\u20130 victory over France to earn the gold medal.\n\nThe stunned French suggested that the U.S. team tour France, which they did; winning three out of the four matches they played. Between 1920 and 1924, however, rugby union virtually disappeared once again in the U.S., as American football soared in popularity.\n\n[[File:1924 France vs USA rugby match.jpg|thumb|left|250px|France vs U.S. rugby match during the 1924 Summer Olympics]]\nThe [[1924 Summer Olympics|1924 Paris Olympics]] caused France to challenge the U.S. to defend its title. Once again, the U.S. Olympic Committee granted permission but no funds. Nonetheless, seven players of the 1920 team dusted off their boots, raised $20,000, found 15 new players including some American football players who had never played in a rugby union match. The assembled U.S. team was again based heavily from Northern California, with 9 Stanford alumni, 5 from Santa Clara, and 3 from Cal.<ref name=\"californiagoldenblogs.com\"/> The team headed for England to play some tuneup matches, where they were beaten four times.\n\nThe French Olympic Committee (FOC) had scheduled the rugby event to kick off the 1924 Paris Games at Colombes Stadium in Paris.  Romania and the U.S. were expected to provide only token opposition for the European champions. On Sunday, May 11, the U.S. pounded Romania 39 to 0, including nine tries.\n\n[[File:USA 1924 rugby team.jpg|right|thumb|250px|The U.S. team that won gold in the [[1924 Summer Olympics]] in Paris]]\nThe final was played at Colombes Stadium on May 18 before an estimated crowd of 30,000 - 50,000 that had gathered to watch the rugby final and the awarding of the first medal of the 1924 Olympics.<ref name=\"californiagoldenblogs.com\"/><ref>U.S. Team is Hissed by French When it Wins Olympic Title, ''N.Y. Times'', May 19, 1924</ref> Bookmakers set the odds at five to one with a 20-point spread.<ref>[http://wesclark.com/rrr/1924_olympics_2.html Rugby at the 1924 Olympics]. Retrieved April 10, 2015.</ref> However, the Americans were not intimidated, and the American captain Babe Slater wrote in his diary before the match \"we are sure going to let them know they have been in a battle.\"<ref name=\"californiagoldenblogs.com\"/> Despite the odds, the U.S. team started well, led by captain Colby \"Babe\" Slater, and led 3\u20130 at the half. Heavy tackling by the Americans, derived from American football, intimidated and exhausted the French, as the U.S. scored four tries in the second half to defeat the French 17\u20133.<ref>[http://www.espnscrum.com/scrum/rugby/story/167592.html \"Olympic Rugby: Rugby and the Olympics\"], ESPN Scrum, July 26, 2012.</ref> Rare vintage film footage of the 1924 gold medal match was released in the documentary, \"A Giant Awakens: the Rise of American Rugby\".\n\nShortly after the 1924 Olympics, however, the International Olympic Committee (IOC) removed rugby union as an Olympic sport. Without the Olympic incentive, the sport's growth in America collapsed and the game remained dormant.\n\n==Modern history==\n{{See also|Rugby union in the United States|The United States at the Rugby World Cup}}\n\n===The 1960s and 1970s===\nThe sport then enjoyed a renaissance, beginning in the 1960s and continuing through the 1970s. This created the need for a national governing body to represent the United States in the international rugby community. The United States of America Rugby Football Union (now known as USA Rugby) was formed in 1975 by four territorial organizations (Pacific Coast, West, Midwest, and East).<ref name=\"SCRFU History\">[http://www.scrfu.org/documents/scrfu-history/ SCRFU History] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017095741/http://www.scrfu.org/documents/scrfu-history/ |date=October 17, 2014 }}, Southern California RFU. Retrieved September 13, 2014.</ref> The first Eagles match was played in Anaheim in 1976 against Australia, the Wallabies won 24\u201312.<ref name=\"SCRFU History\"/>\n\nThe U.S. also performed well against France in Chicago, losing the game 33\u201314. The next season the Eagles played two internationals, one against England (XV-not capped) at [[Twickenham]] on their [[1977 United States rugby union tour of England]], which they lost 37\u201311, and the other against Canada, which they also lost, 17\u20136. The U.S. played the Canadians again in 1978, and defeated them 12\u20137 in Baltimore. They then travelled to Canada in 1979 and lost 19\u201312 in Toronto.\n\n===The 1980s===\nThe U.S. national team came to further prominence during the 1980s, and from the start of the decade, were playing a notably larger number of games every season. They did however lose all three of their games in 1980, all at home. They could not muster up a win in 1981 either, losing 3\u20136 to Canada, and 7\u201338 to South Africa. In 1982, the U.S. drew Canada 3\u20133. They travelled to Australia in 1983 to play the Wallabies, and lost 49\u20133 in Sydney. The U.S. played its first-ever match against Japan in 1985, winning 16\u201315 at the Prince Chichibu Memorial Stadium.<ref>[http://www.irb.com/mm/document/tournament/mediazone/02/06/78/68/20130621japvusa.pdf IRB Match Preview: Japan v USA] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130626163902/http://www.irb.com/mm/document/tournament/mediazone/02/06/78/68/20130621japvusa.pdf |date=June 26, 2013 }}, June 2013.</ref>\n\nThe U.S. participated in 1987 in the [[1987 Rugby World Cup|first ever Rugby World Cup]] in New Zealand and Australia. The U.S. were in Pool 1, alongside co-hosts Australia, England and Japan. The U.S. won their first ever World Cup game, defeating Japan 21\u201318 at Ballymore Stadium in Brisbane, with fullback Ray Nelson scoring 13 points.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/rugby_world_cup/team_pages/usa/2992399.stm \"USA play a different ball game\"], BBC Sport, September 26, 2003.</ref> The U.S. lost both subsequent matches; 47\u201312 against the Wallabies and 34\u20136 against England. The U.S. finished third in the pool, out of contention for the quarterfinals.\n\nThe Eagles first met Wales at Cardiff in November 1987 as the final match of their [[1987 United States rugby union tour of Wales|1987 tour]], where Wales, who had just finished third in the inaugural Rugby World Cup, enjoyed a 46\u20130 win. In 1988, the Eagles had mixed success in their tour of Europe, defeating Romania but losing to the Soviet Union.<ref name=\"Rugby Mag 2012\">[http://www.rugbymag.com/usa-men/6485-notes-on-usa-v-romania.html \"Notes on USA v Romania\"], Rugby Mag, November 23, 2012.</ref>\n\n===The 1990s===\nThe U.S. notched three consecutive wins from September 1990 to May 1991 \u2014 all against Japan \u2014 for the first three-match win streak in U.S. team history.<ref name=\"Test matches - Team records - USA\">[http://stats.espnscrum.com/statsguru/rugby/stats/index.html?class=1;spanmin1=27+Mar+1981;spanval1=span;team=11;template=results;type=team;view=match Test matches - Team records - USA], ESPN Scrum. Retrieved September 26, 2015.</ref>\n\nThe U.S. made their way through a qualifying tournament to reach the [[1991 Rugby World Cup]] in the United Kingdom, pooled with defending champions New Zealand, hosts England, and Italy in a tough group. In their first match of the tournament, Italy defeated them 30\u20139. Next, New Zealand defeated them 46\u20136. Hosts England won 37\u20139 at Twickenham. The U.S. finished fourth in the pool.\n\nIn round one of the Americas qualifying tournament for the [[1995 Rugby World Cup]] the U.S. defeated Bermuda 60\u20133 to advance to round two. Argentina defeated the Eagles twice in close games in the series to qualify, leaving the U.S. missing out on the [[1995 Rugby World Cup]] in South Africa.\n\nThe Eagles went close to beating a major rugby nation in a match against Australia at Riverside in 1993 when the U.S. lost 22\u201326.\n\nThe Eagles had a successful tour of Europe in 1998, beating Spain and Portugal.<ref name=\"Rugby Mag 2012\"/> Also in 1998, the U.S. played Fiji for the first time, losing 9\u201318 in Suva.<ref name=\"irb.com\">[http://www.irb.com/mm/document/tournament/mediazone/02/06/76/66/20130618fijivusa.pdf IRB Match Preview: Fiji v USA], June 2013.</ref>\n\nThe Eagles set out to qualify for the [[1999 Rugby World Cup]] in Wales. In round four of the Americas qualifying tournament in Buenos Aires, the United States lost 52\u201324 to Argentina and 31\u201314 to Canada, but defeated Uruguay 21\u201316 in their last game to qualify for the 1999 tournament. The U.S. played in the 1999 Pacific Rim Championship, notching its first-ever victories over Fiji (25\u201314) and Tonga (30\u201310).<ref name=\"irb.com\"/>\n\nThe Eagles entered the [[1999 Rugby World Cup]] in pool E alongside Australia, Ireland and Romania. In their first game, the United States went down 53\u20138 to Ireland. They then lost to Romania 27\u201325. Australia defeated the Eagles 55\u201319 in their final game of the tournament, seeing the Eagles finish fourth in the pool. The Eagles, however, had the honor of being the only side to score a try against the eventual champions, Australia, during the entire tournament.<ref>[http://rugbyworldcup-argentina2023.blogspot.com/2015/05/retro-friday-juan-grobler-scores-for.html \"Retro Friday: Juan Grobler scores for USA v Australia in 1999\"], Rugby World Cup - Argentina 2023, May 22, 2015.</ref>\n\n===The 2000s===\nIn [[2003 Rugby World Cup qualifying|qualifying matches]] for the 2003 Rugby World Cup the U.S. finished third in the Americas. The U.S. won the repechage and qualified for the 2003 tournament by beating [[Spain national rugby union team|Spain]] 62\u201313 and 58\u201313. The Super Powers Cup was first contested in 2003 between Japan, Russia and the United States.<ref>[http://www.espnscrum.com/scrum/rugby/story/46696.html \"USA hammers Japan\"], ESPN Scrum, May 18, 2003.</ref> The U.S. then followed up with victories over [[Japan national rugby union team|Japan]] and Canada. This was the first time the Eagles had won four consecutive tests since making their international debut in 1976.<ref name=\"Test matches - Team records - USA\"/>\n\nAt the [[2003 Rugby World Cup]] the Eagles finished fourth of five in their pool. In the first match against Fiji, the Americans led 13\u20133 early in the second half, but Fiji regained the lead and secured a 19\u201318 win, with the Eagles suffering their ninth consecutive World Cup loss. The U.S. then lost to Scotland.  The Americans defeated Japan 39\u201326, behind 17 points by Mike Hercus, for their first win in a Rugby World Cup since 1987 (also against Japan).<ref>[http://www.espnscrum.com/onthisday/rugby/story/104549.html \"Wallabies send All Blacks home\"], ESPN Scrum. Retrieved March 24, 2015.</ref> The U.S. closed the tournament with a loss to France, concluding the tournament with a 1\u20133 record.\n\nThe 2004 Super Powers Cup saw the addition of Canada. The U.S. beat Russia in the third-place play-off. The U.S. [[2004 United States rugby union tour|toured Europe in November 2004]], losing 55\u20136 to Ireland and 43\u201325 to Italy. The 2005 Super Cup took part between the U.S., Canada, Japan and Romania. The U.S. lost 30\u201326 to Canada but beat a Romanian team stripped of their France-based players 23\u201316 in the third place play-off.\n[[File:USA Eagles Mascot Churchill Cup 2010.jpg|thumb|160px|Eagles Mascot Churchill Cup 2010|The U.S. Eagle mascot during [[2010 Churchill Cup]].]]\n\nThe U.S. campaign to [[2007 Rugby World Cup - Americas qualification|qualify]] for the [[2007 Rugby World Cup]] began in 2006. The U.S. lost 56\u20137 to Canada, resulting in a home/away play-off against Uruguay. The U.S. defeated Uruguay 42\u201313 in the first match and 26\u20137 in the second to send them through to the Rugby World Cup.<ref>[http://www.espnscrum.com/scrum/rugby/story/65972.html \"USA secures place at RWC'07\"], ESPN Scrum, October 8, 2006. Retrieved March 24, 2015.</ref>\n\nIn the [[2007 Rugby World Cup]], the U.S. joined England, Samoa, South Africa and Tonga in Pool A. The Eagles, ranked 13th in the world standings, lost all 4 games in [[2007 Rugby World Cup - Pool A|Pool A]], scoring 1 bonus point in the game against Samoa. Coached by New Zealander [[Peter Thorburn]], the Eagles started off with tough match against the defending world champions England, losing 28\u201310.  The U.S. was then beaten by Tonga 25\u201315, lost to Samoa 25\u201321, and lost their final match to highly favored South Africa 64\u201315. The Eagles, however, had a major highlight in the South Africa match. After a [[Todd Clever]] interception and a pair of passes, [[Takudzwa Ngwenya]] sped down the sideline and outran the speedster [[Bryan Habana]] to score a try that received Try of the Year honors at the 2007 [[IRB Awards]].<ref>[http://www.rugbyworld.com/countries/rest-of-the-world/rugby-world-cup-2011-usas-story-14387 \"Rugby World Cup 2011: USA\u2019s story\"], Rugby World, August 1, 2011. Retrieved March 24, 2015.</ref>\n\nFollowing the resignation of [[Scott Johnson (rugby coach)|Scott Johnson]], on March 5, 2009 [[Eddie O'Sullivan]] was named the new national coach.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/timeline/rugby/story/92941.html |title=O'Sullivan lands Eagles job |work=ESPN |date=March 5, 2009 |accessdate=December 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Eagles finished a solid 2009 campaign at a mark of 4\u20135, with a 4\u20133 record in full internationals. In the [[2009 Churchill Cup]], the Eagles lost to Ireland and Wales, but defeated Georgia to take home the Bowl.<ref>[http://www.rugby365.com/article/42164-churchill-cup-returns-to-america  \"Churchill Cup returns to America\"], Rugby 365, February 22, 2010. Retrieved April 10, 2015.</ref>\n\n===The 2011 Rugby World Cup cycle===\nThe Eagles split a [[2011 Rugby World Cup qualifying|World Cup qualifying series]] with Canada, but lost on aggregate points. The Eagles then faced Uruguay in a two-game playoff. In November 2009, the United States booked their place at the [[2011 Rugby World Cup]] with two wins against [[Uruguay national rugby union team|Uruguay]], winning the home leg 27\u20136 in Florida.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/8372808.stm|title=Eagles claim 2011 World Cup berth |date=2009-11-22|work=BBC Sport |accessdate=2009-11-22}}</ref>\n\nThe Eagles played 7 matches in 2010: 3 home matches in June at the Churchill Cup, finishing with a 1-2 record, and 4 matches in Europe in the Fall, finishing 1\u20133.\nIn the June [[2010 Churchill Cup]], the US beat Russia 39\u201322, before losing to the England Saxons 32\u20139 and France A 24\u201310. \nFor the [[2010 end of year rugby tests|November 2010 tests]], the Eagles traveled to Europe. The Eagles defeated [[Portugal national rugby union team|Portugal]] 22\u201317,<ref>[http://en.espn.co.uk/scrum/rugby/match/122064.html UNITED STATES OF AMERICA TOUR]. Retrieved April 10, 2015.</ref> but lost to [[Scotland A national rugby union team|Scotland A]] 25\u20130,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eaglesxv.com/games/end-of-year-tour-game-number-2|title=Loading....|publisher=|accessdate=September 21, 2015}}</ref> and lost to [[Georgia national rugby union team|Georgia]] 19\u201317.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eaglesxv.com/games/last-game-of-2010|title=Loading....|publisher=|accessdate=September 21, 2015}}</ref>  \nThe Eagles finished 2010 ranked 16th in the world,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.irb.com/rankings/archive/date=2010-12-27/histranking.html |title=International Rugby Board \u2013 World Rankings: Archive \u2013 Detail |publisher=Irb.com |date=December 27, 2010 |accessdate=October 17, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140320070509/http://www.irb.com/rankings/archive/date=2010-12-27/histranking.html |archive-date=March 20, 2014 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and with a record in test matches of 2 wins (Russia, Portugal) and 1 loss (Georgia).\n\nThe buildup to the [[2011 Rugby World Cup]] started in June with three matches in the [[2011 Churchill Cup|Churchill Cup]].  The Eagles dropped their first matches to the [[England Saxons]] 87\u20138<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnscrum.com/churchill-cup-2011/rugby/match/140098.html |title=Rugby Union \u2013 ESPN Scrum \u2013 England Saxons v United States of America at Northampton, Jun 4, 2011 |publisher=ESPN Scrum |accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref> and to [[Tonga national rugby union team|Tonga]] 44\u201313,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbymag.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1173&catid=39&Itemid=194 |title=USA Poor in Loss to Tonga |publisher=Rugbymag.com |date=June 8, 2011 |accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref> before defeating Russia 32\u201325.<ref name=\"rugbymag.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbymag.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1249&catid=39&Itemid=194 |title=USA Wins Bowl at Churchill Cup |publisher=Rugbymag.com |date=June 18, 2011 |accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref> 2011 was the final Churchill Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnscrum.com/churchill-cup-2011/rugby/story/141830.html |title=Churchill Cup 2011 News : Final bow for Churchill Cup &#124; Live Rugby News |publisher=ESPN Scrum |accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref>\nThe Eagles finalized their [[2011 Rugby World Cup]] preparations with three test matches in August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbymag.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1274:50-player-pool-for-world-cup&catid=39:usa-men&Itemid=194 |title=50-Player Pool for World Cup |publisher=Rugbymag.com |date=June 21, 2011 |accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref> The Eagles lost to Canada 28\u201322,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbymag.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1621:canada-comes-back-to-beat-usa&catid=39:usa-men&Itemid=194 |title=Canada Comes Back to Beat USA |publisher=Rugbymag.com |date=August 6, 2011 |accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref> lost their second match against Canada 27\u20137.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbymag.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1698:eagles-squander-opportunity-against-canada&catid=39:usa-men&Itemid=194 |title=Eagles Squander Opportunity Against Canada |publisher=Rugbymag.com |date=August 13, 2011 |accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref> and lost to Japan 20\u201314.  The Eagles had a 1\u20135 record in test matches for the year in their preparations for the 2011 Rugby World Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbymag.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1740:japan-edges-usa-in-rain&catid=39:usa-men&Itemid=194 |title=Japan Edges USA in Rain |publisher=Rugbymag.com |date=August 22, 2011 |accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Australia vs USA 2011 RWC (2).jpg|thumb|right|[[Australia national rugby union team|Australia]] scrum against the U.S. at the 2011 RWC.]]\nIn their [[2011 Rugby World Cup#Pool C|2011 Rugby World Cup]] opening match against [[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland]] the Eagles defense initially held, before conceding their first try at the 39' mark.  The final tally was 22\u201310.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbymag.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1908&catid=39&Itemid=194 |title=Irish in Battle with Eagles, but Win |publisher=Rugbymag.com |date=September 11, 2011 |accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref>\nThe Eagles came into the World Cup with their measuring mark for success as being a win over Russia. The Americans took a 10\u20133 lead into the half, and held on to win 13\u20136.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbymag.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1962:usa-edges-russia-in-world-cup&catid=39:usa-men&Itemid=194 |title=USA Edges Russia in World Cup |publisher=Rugbymag.com |date=September 15, 2011 |accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref>\nFor their third match, Australia dominated, leading to the final result of 67\u20135, the worst defeat a U.S. team has ever suffered to Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbymag.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2045&catid=39&Itemid=194 |title=Wallabies Much Too Much for Eagles |publisher=Rugbymag.com |date=September 23, 2011 |accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref>\nThe final match saw the Eagles playing [[Italy national rugby union team|Italy]] for a third-place finish in Pool C.  The Italians finished with a 27\u201310 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugbymag.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2103:usa-brave-in-27-10-loss-to-italy&catid=39:usa-men&Itemid=194 |title=USA Brave in 27\u201310 Loss to Italy |publisher=Rugbymag.com |date=September 27, 2011 |accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref>  The defeat marked the end of the 2011 Rugby World Cup for the U.S.\n\nThe Eagles finished 2011 with a record of 2\u20137 in full tests. The performances in the Rugby World Cup showed improvement, and the win over Russia left the team with a 1\u20133 RWC record and feeling as a modest success. The World Cup also saw prop [[Mike MacDonald (rugby union)|Mike MacDonald]] become both the most capped Eagle in World Cup play (11 caps) and the most capped Eagle of all time at 65 caps.  Also notable was the performance of lock [[John van der Giessen]], who achieved the most lineout steals of all players in the 2011 Rugby World Cup, despite appearing in only three matches.<ref>Rugby World, Dec. 2011, page 40.</ref>\n\n===The 2015 Rugby World Cup cycle===\nThe Eagles played three matches in North America during the [[2012 mid-year rugby test series|2012 June international window]]. This was a regular series of international tests for the United States against Tier 1 (Italy) and Tier 2 (Canada, Georgia) opponents, as the Churchill Cup is no longer held.  The highlights of the June tests were a win over higher-ranked Georgia, and a match against Italy at [[BBVA Compass Stadium]] in Houston that drew a record crowd of 17,214.<ref>[http://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/For-Houston-rugby-fans-home-turf-is-gaining-5535310.php \"For Houston rugby fans, home turf is gaining ground\"], ''Houston Chronicle'', June 6, 2014.</ref>\nThe Eagles also played three matches in Europe during the [[2012 end-of-year rugby union tests|November 2012 tests]]. The Eagles finished their European tour with 2 wins (Romania, Russia) and 1 loss (Tonga) \u2014 the first time since 1998 that the Eagles had concluded a European tour with a winning record \u2014 and improved in ranking from 17th to 16th.<ref name=\"Rugby Mag 2012\"/>\n\n[[File:M\u0101ori All Blacks against the USA Eagles at PPL Park.jpg|thumb|right|235px|The U.S. v. the [[M\u0101ori All Blacks]] at PPL Park in 2013.]]\n\nThe U.S. played five matches during the June 2013 international test window, with one test match against Ireland and four matches as part of the [[2013 IRB Pacific Nations Cup]].  The U.S. started with competitive matches against Canada (9\u201316), Ireland (12\u201315), and Tonga (9\u201318), but finished with double-digit losses against Fiji (10\u201335) and Japan (20\u201338), and sliding to #18 in the rankings.\nIn August 2013, the U.S. played a home-and-away series against Canada as part of [[2015 Rugby World Cup qualifying|qualifying]] for the 2015 Rugby World Cup. The U.S. lost both matches by an aggregate score of 20\u201340, meaning the U.S. must play Uruguay in 2014 as part of 2015 RWC qualifying.\nIn November 2013, the U.S. lost 19-29 to the [[M\u0101ori All Blacks]] at [[PPL Park]] in Philadelphia before a sold-out crowd of 18,500.<ref>{{cite news|last=Shannon|first=Kris|title=NZ Maori escape against Eagles|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=11154762|accessdate=November 10, 2013|newspaper=The New Zealand Herald|date=November 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThroughout late 2013 and early 2014, a number of U.S. players signed contracts to play professionally overseas. Of the players called into the U.S. national team in March 2014 for two home-and-away [[2015 Rugby World Cup \u2013 Americas qualification|2015 Rugby World Cup qualifying]] matches against Uruguay, 14 of the 26 were playing professionally overseas, with 10 playing professionally in England.<!-- Sixteen players were playing outside the U.S., but two of these were playing in amateur leagues \u2014 Nick Wallace with James Bay in Canada, and Tom Coolican with Richmond in England's 3rd division.--><ref>[http://www.thisisamericanrugby.com/2014/03/eagles-selected-for-first-uruguay-match.html \"Eagles Selected For First Uruguay Match\"], This Is American Rugby, March 15, 2014. Retrieved March 20, 2014.</ref>\nThe Eagles defeated Uruguay 59\u201340 on aggregate over two tests during 2014 to qualify for the [[2015 Rugby World Cup]]. During the June 2014 test window, the U.S. played competitive matches against higher ranked Scotland and Japan, and the test window culminated with a 38\u201335 victory over Canada. Subsequently, in November 2014 the Eagles were defeated 74\u20136 by New Zealand in a match played in front of a crowd of more than 61,000 spectators at [[Soldier Field]], [[Chicago]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/nov/07/wallabies-us-rugby-all-blacks-chicago-test |title=Wallaby greats say US 'sleeping giant' of rugby and hail All Blacks' Chicago Test |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=November 7, 2014 |website=[[theguardian.com]]|accessdate=November 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Eagles began a lengthy assembly in build up to the 2015 Rugby World Cup with the [[2015 World Rugby Pacific Nations Cup|2015 Pacific Nations Cup]]. On July 18, the U.S. dropped the opening PNC match 21\u201316 to [[Samoa national rugby union team|Samoa]].<ref name=\"auto1\">[http://www.goffrugbyreport.com/news/usa-comeback-falls-short \"USA Comeback Falls Short\"], Goff Rugby Report,  July 18, 2015.</ref> The team bounced back to upset [[Japan national rugby union team|Japan]] 23\u201318. The Eagles, however, fell to [[Tonga national rugby union team|Tonga]] in the final preliminary match for the PNC 33\u201319. In the resulting fifth-place match, the Eagles edged rival [[Canada national rugby union team|Canada]] 15\u201313. The victory was the second consecutive over team Canada. Three weeks later, Canada and the U.S. met again in a World Cup warmup match. For the first time, the U.S. laid claim to a three-match win streak over team Canada after defeating the Canadians 41-23.<ref>[http://en.espn.co.uk/scrum/rugby/story/272483.html \"USA down Canada 41-23 in World Cup tune-up\"], ESPN UK, August 22, 2015.</ref> Continuing on the road to the World Cup, the U.S. faced off against [[English Premiership (rugby union)|English Premiership]] side [[Harlequin F.C.|Harlequins]], where the Americans fell to the visitors 24\u201319.<ref>[http://www.rugbytoday.com/elite/eagles-fall-short-harlequins \"Eagles Fall Short to Harlequins\"], Rugby Today, August 30, 2015.</ref> The Eagles returned to [[Soldier Field]] to compete against the #2 ranked [[Australia national rugby union team|Australia Wallabies]]. The Americans trailed 14\u201310 at the half. In the second half, the Wallabies capitalized on American errors and pushed the match out of reach: Australia 47, the U.S. 10.<ref>[http://www.rugbytoday.com/elite/eagles-fall-wallabies-last-rwc-tune \"Eagles Fall to Wallabies in Last RWC Tune-Up\"], Rugby Today, September 5, 2015.</ref>\n\n===Professional era (2016\u2013present)===\n{{Main|PRO Rugby|Major League Rugby}}\nThe Professional Rugby Organization (PRO Rugby) began a professional rugby competition in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.prorugby.org/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=November 14, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151114030155/http://www.prorugby.org/ |archive-date=November 14, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Five teams played a 10-match schedule from April to July. Each PRO Rugby team had a quota for overseas players and U.S. Eagles internationals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/nov/09/us-professional-rugby-union-league|title=US professional rugby union competition to begin play in April|first=Martin|last=Pengelly|date=November 9, 2015|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.americasrugbynews.com/2015/11/20/4875/|title=Second PRO Rugby Team Confirmed for California|date=November 21, 2015}}</ref> The U.S. national team included 14 professionals in the starting lineup for the June 2015 test against Italy \u2014 six U.S.-based professionals and eight overseas professionals.<ref>[http://www.rugbytoday.com/elite/lineups-named-usa-vs-italy \"LINEUPS NAMED FOR USA VS. ITALY\"], Rugby Today, Pat Clifton, June 16, 2016.</ref> PRO Rugby did not last long, however, with the competition folding after only one season.\n\nProfessional rugby returned in 2018 with the advent of Major League Rugby, a seven-team competition that runs from April to early July. U.S. head coach Gary Gold called up an all-professional squad for the June 2018 tests, drawing from a mix of Major League Rugby players and overseas professionals. During the June 2018 tests, the U.S. defeated Scotland 30\u201329 to give the U.S. its first win over a Tier 1 nation since beating France at the 1924 Olympics.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}} In the November tests, the U.S added wins against Canada (42\u201317), Samoa (30\u201329), and Romania (31\u20135) to ensure their longest full international test win streak in team history with 10. The streak ended with a defeat to Ireland in Dublin. In their first match of the [[2019 Rugby World Cup]], they were defeated (45-7) against [[England national rugby union team|England]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/sep/26/england-usa-rugby-world-cup-pool-c-match-report|title=Cokanasiga helps England crush USA as Quill sees World Cup\u2019s first red card|last=Stadium|first=Robert Kitson at Kobe Misaki|date=2019-09-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-09-26|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Recent results==\nThe following table shows the results of the U.S. national team during the previous 24 months, as well as upcoming fixtures.\n\nNotes:\n* Opponent rank is listed as of the date of the match.\n* <span style=\"background:#cfc;\">Green</span> shading indicates a win or tie against a higher ranked opponent. <span style=\"background:#fbb;\">Red</span> shading indicates a loss or tie against a lower ranked opponent.\n* '''Bolded''' attendance figures indicate the match is one of the top five highest attended home matches in U.S. national team history.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!width=70|Date\n!width=120|Opponent\n!width=40|[[World Rugby Rankings|Opp Rank]]\n!width=65|Result\n!width=215|Venue\n!width=45|Attendance\n!width=140|Event\n!width=115|Top U.S. Scorer\n|-style=\n| 2020-09-12\n| align=left | {{ruA|ARG}}\n| N/A\n| \n| align=left | {{flagdeco|ARG}} TBA\n| \n| [[2020 Americas Rugby Championsip|ARC]]\n| \n|-style=\n| 2020-09-05\n| align=left | {{ru|BRA}}\n| \n| \n| align=left | {{flagdeco|BRA}} TBA\n| \n| [[2020 Americas Rugby Championsip|ARC]]\n| \n|-style=\n| 2020-08-29\n| align=left | {{ru|URU}}\n| \n| \n| align=left | {{flagdeco|USA}} TBA\n| \n| [[2020 Americas Rugby Championsip|ARC]]\n| \n|-style=\n| 2020-08-22\n| align=left | {{ru|CHI}}\n| \n| \n| align=left | {{flagdeco|USA}} TBA\n| \n| [[2020 Americas Rugby Championsip|ARC]]\n| \n|-style=\n| 2020-08-15\n| align=left | {{ru|CAN}}\n| \n| \n| align=left | {{flagdeco|USA}} TBA\n| \n| [[2020 Americas Rugby Championsip|ARC]]\n| \n|-style=\n| 2020-07-11\n| align=left | {{nowrap|{{flagdeco|FRA}} [[French Barbarians]]}}\n| N/A\n| \n| align=left | {{flagdeco|USA}} [[New York City]]\n| \n| [[2020 July rugby union tests|mid-year tests]]\n| \n|-style=\n| 2020-07-04\n| align=left | {{ru|ITA}}\n| \n| \n| align=left | {{flagdeco|USA}} TBA\n| \n| [[2020 July rugby union tests|mid-year tests]]\n| \n|-\n| 2019-10-13\n| align=left | {{ru|TON}}\n| 13\n| L, 19-31\n| align=left | {{flagdeco|JPN}} [[Hanazono Rugby Stadium]]\n| 22,012\n| [[2019 Rugby World Cup Pool C|World Cup]]\n| [[Mike Te'o|Te'o]] (10)\n|-\n| 2019-10-09\n| align=left | {{ru|ARG}}\n| 10\n| L, 17-47\n| align=left | {{flagdeco|JPN}} [[Kumagaya Rugby Ground]]\n| 24,337\n| [[2019 Rugby World Cup Pool C|World Cup]]\n| [[Blaine Scully|Scully]] (10)\n|-\n| 2019-10-02\n| align=left | {{ru|FRA}}\n| 7\n| L, 9-33\n| align=left | {{flagdeco|JPN}} [[Level5 Stadium|Fukuoka Hakatanomori Stadium]]\n| 17,660\n| [[2019 Rugby World Cup Pool C|World Cup]]\n| [[AJ MacGinty|MacGinty]] (9)\n|-\n| 2019-09-26\n| align=left | {{ru|ENG}}\n| 3\n| L, 7-45\n| align=left | {{flagdeco|JPN}} [[Noevir Stadium Kobe|Kobe Misaki Stadium]]\n| 27,194\n| [[2019 Rugby World Cup Pool C|World Cup]]\n| [[Bryce Campbell (rugby union)|Campbell]] (5)\n|-\n| 2019-09-07\n| align=left | {{ru|CAN}}\n| 21\n| W, 20-15\n| align=left | {{flagdeco|CAN}} [[BC Place]]\n| \n| [[2019 Rugby World Cup warm-up matches|RWC warm-up]]<ref name=Warmup>{{cite web |url=https://www.usarugby.org/2019/05/u-s-mens-national-team-15s-to-face-rival-canada-in-vancouver-as-final-test-match-before-rugby-world-cup-japan-2019/ |title=U.S. Men\u2019s National Team 15s to face rival-Canada in Vancouver as final test match before Rugby World Cup Japan 2019 |last=Tabani |first=Aalina |date=May 16, 2019 |publisher=[[USA Rugby]] |access-date=May 28, 2019}}</ref>\n| [[Cam Dolan|Dolan]] / [[Dylan Fawsitt|Fawsitt]] / [[Martin Iosefo|Iosefo]] / [[Will Magie|Magie]] (5)\n|-\n| 2019-08-10\n| align=l