 = {{formatnum:103,600|R}}\n| pop_est_as_of=2015\n| pop_est_footnotes=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.townplan.gov.my/epublisiti/drsnp2040/DRAF%20RS%20PERAK.pdf|title=Rancangan Struktur Negeri Perak 2040|format=PDF|page=316|access-date=28 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180328165042/http://www.townplan.gov.my/epublisiti/drsnp2040/DRAF%20RS%20PERAK.pdf|archive-date=28 March 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|timezone=[[Malaysian Standard Time|MST]]\n|utc_offset=+8\n|timezone_DST=Not observed\n| utc_offset_DST               = +8\n|postal_code_type=[[Postal codes in Malaysia|Postcode]]\n|postal_code=316xx-319xx\n|area_code=+6-05\n|area_code_type          = [[Telephone numbers in Malaysia|Calling code]]\n|registration_plate_type =[[Vehicle registration plates of Malaysia|Vehicle registration plates]]\n|registration_plate=A\n}}\n\nThe '''Kampar District''' is a [[List of districts in Malaysia|district]] in [[Perak]], [[Malaysia]]. It was a district on 21 May 2009 after the Sultan of Perak declared Kampar the state's 10th district, which is the smaller district in the state. Its local government is [[Kampar District Council]] based in the town of [[Kampar, Perak|Kampar]].\n\nHistorically, Kampar District was once famous for its tin, being one of the major tin producers in the 18th century. In the 19th century, Kinta district was famous for its tin. It was the number one tin producing valley in the world.{{fact|date=December 2017}}\n\n==Administrative divisions==\n[[File:Map of Kampar District, Perak.svg|250px|thumb|Map of Kampar District]]\nKampar District is divided into 2 [[mukim]]s, which are:<ref name=\"perak.gov.my\">{{cite web|url=http://pdtkampar.perak.gov.my/info-korporat/latar-belakang-daerah|title=Pejabat Daerah dan Tanah Kampar - Latar Belakang Daerah|website=pdtkampar.perak.gov.my}}</ref>\n* [[Kampar, Perak|Kampar]]\n* [[Teja, Perak|Teja]]\n\n== Demographics ==\nThe following is based on Department of Statistics Malaysia 2010 census.{{my10|2}}\